It's a great idea but doesn't work in practice. Either the nozzle on the can is poorly designed or there is some issue with quality control, but I have tried cleaning my table with three of these cans now and every time, glops of foam dripped from the nozzle onto my cloth and ended up leaving an unsightly stain. The can (when shaken up well) does dispense an even flow of foam on the table, but also some collects on the nozzle and then drips onto the cloth. I have tried different methods of preventing this but to no effect. Sure the product restores the colour and and gets rid of SOME of the chalk (you still need to vacuum first!) but it takes AGES to dry!
I have just replaced my cloth and will no longer use this product. Instead, I brush the rails, vacuum the table's playing surface, then wipe a DAMP (not wet) cloth gently over it. On a wool cloth, the damp cloth is good for keeping it tight too.  I find water dries MUCH faster than the Quick-Clean anyway. Then I vacuum any lint from the cloth I used off the table and it leaves it looking like new! It plays beautifully too. I must say that Quick-Clean is pretty good on the wrap on my cue though. But then again so is (you guessed) WATER! Don't waste your money folks!

I purchased this Fobus holster for my Glock 19 to replace my Blackhawk SERPA holster.  The SERPA had been getting bad press for ADs when pressing the button and briskly drawing the weapon in combat situations.  Hence, I went with the Fobus to eliminate the risk of an AD.  It holds the weapon firmly, and works well in concealment.  Unlike the SERPA that requires a button push, however, the Fobus requires a brisk draw by pulling the weapon straight up, to unlock the clamp that holds it in the holster.  This sounds good, right?  Here's the catch - and I thankfully learned it in training.  Otherwise, my friends, I'd be dead now.
In today's training (I am a full time LEO), we got knocked off a bicycle and had to draw and fire at multiple assailants while lying weak side down.  Guess what?  I could not draw the weapon because while laying down, I was not able to pull the weapon straight up in a brisk pull.  After a few frantic seconds and some really powerful yanks, I got it out and engaged the targets.  But, that was pretending to be knocked down and laying on the ground.  Would I have been able to keep my cool and get the weapon out if someone had really punched me, or worse?  I don't think so.  I am -- after writing this review -- actually here on AMZN to purchase a new holster.  Upshot - if you plan to be standing, great, this holster will work.  If you plan to carry your weapon with you everywhere, don't get this holster.  If you get knocked down, or for that matter, if you get down for cover, I can now confirm that you may not be able to draw the weapon. That will get you dead really quickly.
summary: Dangerous in a real encounter........read on

reviewText:
I have had this mug for 5 years. I almost always have it with me - in the car, in my backpack, at my office. I've taken it on so many road trips. Filled it in so many gas stations and podunk cafes on long and quiet highways. The coffee within has powered many late night drives to get back home from a trip to the desert/mountains. I even drove 3,600 miles from Alaska to Colorado with this mug. A great deal of coffee was consumed on that trip. My point is this mug has been around the block.

It is definitely the best mug I have ever owned. I can't actually think of a way to improve it.

- It keeps things very warm. None of this plastic garbage that doesn't actually keep anything warm and absorbs flavors over time..
- It fits nicely in a car cup holder. Which can't always be said for other cups. *cough* Contigo.
- It has a valve that closes. This is so you don't spill molten lava all over yourself and try to sue the gas station attendant that sold the coffee to you.
- It has two openings so it's always easy to drink out of from whatever direction you grab it from.
- It's very durable. I've dropped it on concrete many times and it doesn't really do anything. Use it as a last defense against roadside attacks.
- It's 16oz, a perfect size.
- It's a nice shape to hold in your hand.
- It looks nice.
- This cup will outlast your car, every coffee machine you own, your life, your children's life, and very likely, all of humankind.
- When all has faded to dust, there will still be a Thermos King 16oz cup, half buried in sand, paint eroded away, with lukewarm 7/11 coffee inside.
- You can easily take apart the lid to clean the internals where coffee residue or flavors might start to build up.
- The Thermos logo fell long ago, it was just glued on.
- Like most people, the paint on mine started to come off. Embrace it -- it's a sign of pride for how long you've owned it. You really want it to look like your cup is brand new all the time? No! After a few years I discovered the black paint can be scraped off with a mesh metal kitchen scrubber. With some elbow grease, I scraped off all the paint to have a beautiful chrome mug of bare steel reborn. Like Gandalf the White. Or a snake shedding its skin. Or a butterfly born from the chrysalis. Or a phoenix rising from the ashes.

Seriously. Invest in your future. Buy this mug.
Great fit- room enough for stuff I don't want in my pockets and zippers close towards you so it's visible. Has a top section to slide your phone. Well thought out.

Ordered 9-28-15, easy to assemble and it can be done with the tools provided. Utilized my own which made it easier. My wife loved the elliptical bike and had been using it twice a day. On 2-2-16, I contacted Best Choice Products customer service about the fan wheel starting to wobble. Found that the right side where the chain sprocket is attached had exceptional wear on the plastic part of the fan wheel which caused the wobbling. This is a pre-assembled part of the elliptical bike and I was attempting to get a replacement part. I was advised by customer service that the warranty was only for 60 days but the customer service representative stated she would contact a supervisor concerning the part. On 2-3-16, customer service advised me that a replacement part would be sent and should arrive within 5-7 days. On 2-5-16, we received a replacement elliptical bike. Awesome and professional customer service from Best Choice Products. They are not the manufacturer of this product, it is made in China. However, for a company selling the product, outstanding customer service. Thank You Best Choice Products.

May 2016 Update; The replacement Elliptical Bike was delivered on 2-5-16 and was non-functioning by 5-6-16. Same issue as the first. A big design flaw with the plastic wheel which can not take the strain and/or use with the metal parts, specifically the drive sprocket. The metal "axle" which runs through the center of the plastic wheel requires a fixed metal sleeve so as not to excessively wear out the plastic wheel which causes the wobbling and ultimately renders the Elliptical Bike useless. Changed to one star for the product. Moved on to a major brand and spent the money hoping for better results
summary: Great Customer Service, but BAD product.

I bought this seat to replace the stock seat on my new Cannondale Slice.  The stock seat is not comfortable after more that 20 minutes.

I have an old profile design seat on my MTB that has a similar cut out and I like it. I figured I would give this one a chance, it is reasonably priced and it is similar to the type of saddle I have had good luck with before.  The seat is an INSTANT improvement over the stock saddle.

This saddle works great, very comfortable. The longest I have ridden for so far is just over 1 hour (23 miles) no numbness or serious discomfort at all.

 I can ride for up to 40 minutes without padded bike shorts just wearing my running shorts with zero problems as well.

I will find out if this will work for longer distances (time) over the upcoming winter on the trainer.

The seat has plenty of forward and aft adjustment to fine tune your bike position.

I 100% recommend it.

UPDATE,  I just did a 51 mile ride in a tough route. Hilly, wind and reasonably fast 2 hours and 48 minutes.  Not as comfortable as sitting on the couch to be sure and I was glad to get off the bike BUT very doable and a HUGE improvement over the previous saddle.

UPDATE... I have switched to an Adamo ISM Racing II.  After several adjustments over about 100 miles of riding I am now a believer in the Adamo.  THAT SAID the Adamo costs 3X as much and is about twice as good. Figure it out for yourself if it is worth it.  ALSO, I find the Adamo very comfortable in the aero position BUT less than great in the upright position.  So to conclude the Adamo is what I will probably stick with for triathlon. BUT the  Profile Design is a great first improvement for a new rider over the stock seat.
summary: Great seat for a tri bike

reviewText:
I love this mug. I've had it for several months now and quite honestly I've beaten the crap out of it (still going strong!!!) While it is easily the best mug I've had there are a few things I would change:

1. Lid design makes it hard to see where the vents are. Not a huge deal for some since if you tip it slowly the lid is designed to funnel liquid to the lowest point just fine (but I don't always do that). My fix - I put some tape (reflective tape seems to stick the best) at the 9 and 3 o'clock positions when the vents are at 12 and 6. No more guessing.

2. Design is sleek and smooth which is comfortable to hold but does end up sliding out of the side pockets on my backpack occasionally (resulting in much of the harsh treatment I've put it through). A quick wrap with a bike tube or some rubber bands might fix this but wouldn't be as nice to hold.

3. Seal button can be deceiving. Steam pressure can build up inside pushing the button up to show as sealed when it's not. After bending over to get things with my backpack on and pouring hot tea down my side a few times I've just learned to double check this. Yeah, it took me more than once. Don't laugh.  Ok, laugh.

Regardless of these few things I would absolutely buy the exact same one again without hesitation.

This is a compact weight bench for low-intensity lifters. It's currently sitting on ProSource Puzzle Exercise Mat High Quality EVA Foam Interlocking Tiles, 24 Square Feet, Blue in my garage. Assembly was easy, took about 2 hours and I didn't hurry. I appreciated that all the small parts are shrink-wrapped onto a labeled card; it made it easy to find them. Don't just rip that apart; open them as you need them. In addition to the included hex wrenches, you'll need at the minimum a crescent wrench, a box cutter, and a mallet to put this together; you may also want a ratcheted socket wrench (13/16") to speed things up, and a side cutter to cut the zipties. Don't be afraid to pound with the mallet; this is a tensegrity construction and so the parts don't always line up perfectly. As a weight bench, the bar catches are easy to move, the backboard is wide enough and reasonably padded, and its surface is a nice faux leather vinyl. The bar catches are closer together than the usual bench but as long as you stay aligned there's no concern with a 7" Olympic bar. I don't max out; if I did, I would want a more forgiving type of bench that had the bar catches further apart in case my form started to wobble. I don't see much use for the leg unit. The plastic ends that hold the rubber cushions on are sharp and have to be hammered into place with a mallet, and they still don't hold the cushions very stable. The axle is an ill fit, lists off to one side, and you can't put much weight on it, so I think it is more a novelty item. The side catches hold my 170 lbs of weights no problem, and I don't think I'll be having any trouble using all that weight plus my 200 lb body on this bench, although the vague sticker notes a '300 lb limit'. I'm getting back into lifting after a 25 year hiatus, and I am hoping to get a year or so out of this bench 3 times a week, at which point hopefully I'll have the self-esteem to walk into a real gym and move my workouts there. I think if you're looking for heavier use - maxing out, or 225 lb sets, or a real leg machine, or a 5 year investment - you might be better served to look for a sturdier unit.

You have any waterproof outerwear, like ski jackets or pants, or even rain jackets, this is a must have!! We all know that a good ski jacket isn't cheap, especially for brands like Arcteryx, Marmot, Mountain Hardware, Patagonia, or mid-price range brands like the North Face. If you're out on the mountain a lot during winter time, or hike during summer time, the Nikwax is a must to help keep the jacket/pants look like new. I'm not going to explain how waterproof jacket works, you can read it here ( www.rei.com/learn/expert-advice/rainwear-how-it-works.html), but essentially, you CAN'T use regular detergents to wash your waterproof outwear or else you'll ruin the DWR layer that help prevent the water from getting in.

This Duo-pack comes with 2 different bottles. And I'll briefly summarize the different usages.

Tech wash - This is the first one to use in washing your outerwear. It cleans the dirt that's blocking the tiny pores on the surface of the outerwear so that it revives the breathability (so excessive heat can escape). It claims to add water repellency back to the outerwear as well, meaning renewing the layer of DWR, but not enough to restore the waterproofness back to optimal conditon.

T.X. Direct - this is where you need to perform the second step after the Tech wash. Essentially T.X. Direct contains mostly DWR material to further waterproof your washed outerwear. And that's why this pack comes with 2 different bottles to completely wash and renew your outerwear.

**interesting fact**
If your something like a backpack, and it doesn't have waterproof ability, you can wash it first (with regular detergent or Tech wash), and then use T.X. Direct. It will help repel light rain. It's useful if you hike in the summer and encounter light rain. If you want an easier way, you can also try the spray version (http://www.amazon.com/Nikwax-Fabric-Leather-Spray-On-Waterproofing/dp/B0028EFBLY/ref=sr_1_1?s=apparel&ie=UTF8&qid=1449154066&sr=1-1&nodeID=7141123011)
summary: A must have for ski/snowboard jackets or pants

reviewText:
DISCLAIMER: This product was provided to me by the manufacturer in order to allow me to review it. With that said, I was not compensated in any way for this review, and no promises were made that I would either review this product, or review it positively after receiving it. Please see my profile for more info.

Product:Simply Simily Stainless Steel Water Bottle

General Impressions: This is a nice looking product that has an attractive wave logo and message about recycling. Not too long ago many people started carrying around plastic bottles, which now seem to be the way most Americans get their water. Plastic is harmful to the environment, probably to the people drinking the water, and bottled water is many times more expensive than tap water. In the US nearly everywhere tap water is as good or better than bottled water. To improve the taste I have been using a Brita pitcher with a carbon filter for our already good tap water. This bottle is the perfect companion for a Brita or similar pitcher. I have also always liked the way water tastes in a stainless steel container, I am not totally sure if there is a difference or this is my imagination (probably the later).

Quality of Product: This is a stainless steel water bottle with a plastic cap. I have used similar bottles for sometime. The cap fits tightly and the product appears well made. It is NOT insulated, so even though you could put something hot in it, I wouldnt do it.

Issues: The bottle comes with a small piece of paper warning about putting hot liquids in and being careful if you choose to. While this doesnt surprise me, I just wished people had more common sense than to put boiling liquid into an uninsulated metal container. But I am sure someone has done that more than once.

Comparisons to Other Products: I have seen other similar bottles before, and I think that the logo is a nice touch to distinguish this product. The bottle and cap are very much like other similar products I have seen in both quality and appearance.

Pros:
-Nice quality
-Distinctive logo
-Way cheaper to fill up your own water bottle than to use plastic bottles that are expensive and destructive to the environment.

Cons:
-It isn't insulated?
-Nothing else really
summary: Nice stainless bottle so you can stop using plastic water bottles!

This is not the top of the line in bicycle rack-top bags, but it's a good value for the money. You can buy it at Dick's Sporting Goods but I got it for about $5 less (with free shipping) from Amazon. It attaches securely to the rack with two velcro straps. It looks good and appears to be well made. The size is adequate for day trips; as shown in the photo, the top is expandable. There are also a variety of helpful side compartments. A surprise I hadn't realized when I ordered is that it is actually insulated, too. This is a mid-size rack bag. It is not one of the behemoth bags that allow you to carry your work clothes, shoes, a helmet, and a laptop. But it is also not one of those tiny bags for accessories. It's a nice mid-size bag. It has some helpful extra touches, such as a clip on the back for a "blinky" rear bike light to attach. It also has reflective markings, and comes with a shoulder strap that can be detached.

The only downside is that I like to park and take my bike bag into restaurants or stores; because it uses Velcro straps, it is a slight inconvenience to have to un-do and re-do those each time. The bags that are made to slide directly on to the racks that are made especially for them are probably a bit more convenient in this regard.
summary: Looks good, good capacity for day trips, good value

After years of heavy lifting, I'm surprised I didn't invest in knee sleeves before.  I've had two knee reconstructions, and on a heavy squat day, my knees can start to bother me.  I decided to get knee sleeves in hopes that they would make me feel more stable - which is exactly what this pair has done for me.  I wear these sleeves whenever I'm doing heavy, short sets (3-5 reps of body weight or higher).  I do not wear them for most activity as they do constrain your mobility.  I think they would be somewhat uncomfortable for long-duration activities like running where a knee brace might be more appropriate than a sleeve.

I am 5'2", 120lbs and ordered a small.  They are tight to get on, but definitely put the right pressure on your knee cap so you feel incredibly stable. They are very hard to get on once you're sweaty, so I would recommend putting them on, then flipping them inside out while you warm up (just roll them inside out and let them rest of your calves).  You can then flip them right-side out and into place when you start to lift, without having to tug hard to get them up.

I received this product at a discount in exchange for my honest and unbiased review.
summary: Great for added stability during heavy lifting sessions

reviewText: I am now legal to boat at night...

I bought this revolver as a marksmanship training device.  This resembles the Colt Python or Diamondback revolver except for being single action (you must cock the hammer for each shot).  It takes three times the training time and twice the ammuntion to achieve proficiency with the double-action revolver as it does with the semi-automatic handgun and revolver shooters require more refresher training.  I've only owned and fired two Colt double-action revolvers--the rest have been Smith and Wessons or clones of Smith and Wesson.  So the cylinder rotates "backwards" and I cannot get the feel of the double-action trigger.  There is also the durability issue--this revolver is too flimsy for dynamic tactical training.

However, as a safer alternative training device to a live revolver for handling and basic marksmanship this works well.  It feels good in the hand, if about a quarter the weight of the real revolver.  Trigger pull is short and light--not up to the Colt standards, but adequate for training. I'd place the target no more than ten feet from the shooter and five feet isn't too close.  Wear your safety goggles (not included).  Firing signature is low.  For shooting at moving targets, the low velocity brightly-colored 6mm pellet acts like a tracer bullet in good light.  Being able to fire indoors without a special range and being able to reuse ammunition keeps practice costs low as you master sight alignment and trigger control.  The seperate cartriges are nice for training in revolver handling and loading/unloading exercises.  The cartridges are easy to load, but rough handling will cause the 6mm pellets to fall out.  I ordered an additional package of cartridges so that I could practice reloading.  The pistol lacks durability for dynamic drills, but for a beginner who practices smoothly performing every action perfectly, it works very well.

I commend the adjustable sights--they work like the originals--but be careful to GENTLY adjust the sights.

I was looking for an inexpensive training revolver that I didn't need a formal firearms range for safe practice.  I cannot fire combat drills with this revolver, but I do have a device that permits me to safely shoot indoors at 10 feet and practice sight alignment and trigger control.  I have to load without using a speed loader (can't find one that fits) but that works for the beginner, too.
summary: Colt Revolver Replica for Marksmanship Training

reviewText:
This knife is a close replica of a knife that played a prominent role in the war In Viet Nam. If you're interested in that role and history just search for "MACV-SOG knife" on the web.  I had purchased an inexpensive knockoff of this knife which got me interested in learning more about this historic knife. The more I learned the more I knew I had to have this knife. I know the actual knives varied somewhat over the years, but this SOG S1T-L Bowie 2.0 knife was designed and crafted to accurately represent the appearance and salient features of the original MACV-SOG knife and its successors. Of course over the decades better materials, a titanium coating and advanced manufacturing have contributed to a knife much improved from the 1960's while retaining the uniqueness and qualities of the original.

This knife is very well made. The unique blade is perfectly ground, shaped, polished and sharpened. It is beautifully coated in black titanium nitride (TiNi) as are the cross guard and the butt cap. The handle is made of leather washers slotted and stacked along the blade tang. They are shaped to provide a smooth finish and flat finger grooves along the bottom. The handle is oval shaped and is said to be epoxy coated. There is a hole in the butt cap for a lanyard.

The sheath is well made of high quality leather dyed black and follows the pattern of the original SOG knife sheath with a small pouch on the front that includes a sharpening stone. The retention strap wraps around the top of the cross guard and snaps to the front.

I have only two minor complaints The handle is quite slippery. The finger grooves are helpful, but not quite enough. Also, there is a rivet through the lower portion of the belt loop that attaches the retention strap. As the blade is slid into the sheath the cross guard can slide along the rivet cap which can put a scratch in the cross guard. This can be avoided if the belt loop is pulled back while inserting the blade in the sheath, however, this isn't practical if the sheath is on the belt. I like the knife enough overall to not mark it down for these issues. Carrying and using any knife will cause wear, so either keep it for show or use it and accept the wear. If you like knives, you'll like this one.

reviewText:
I've had this about a month and a half.  I waited for Armalaser to release the TR4 before buying a laser because I really like the way it activates by skin contact without any buttons to push.  Now that I have used it, I really like it.  I am glad I waited.

It fits well on my S&W Shield.  I am new at shooting, but fairly handy with tools.  It took me about 20 to 30 minutes of carefully following the directions to complete the installation.  Now that it is done I realize I could have gone much more quickly, but I was afraid of breaking something.  The FFL who delivered my pistol asked to look at the installation.  His comment: "Looks factory installed."

I took it to a range to test how well it was sighted in.  I test fired groups at 5, 7, 10, and 25 yards, using bean bags to steady and brace each shot.  At the close in, personal defense ranges [5, 7, and 10 yards] my groups were about 2 to 3 inches high, but right on the center line.  I am not surprised because the factory says it is adjusted before shipping for a longer distance.  I plan to re-adjust the aim, probably for 10 yards, on my next trip to the range.  At 25 yards, my groups were awful, but that is not the laser's fault, it is just I am not a good shot at that distance.  I can barely see the target.

The only downside at this point is that the TR4 is still so new that I cannot find any fitted holster for my pistol with the laser installed.  Armalaser has told me they are working with a manufacturer and will email me when they have it set up.  I talked with the president of Comfort-Tuk yesterday and learned he is trying to get a model to send to his mold maker so he can make a holster to fit.  But for now all I can use are generic, non-formed holsters.  The "UTG Ambidextrous Pocket Holster (Small, 3.9-Inch, Black)," available here on Amazon, the BlackHawk size 7 IWB from a local store, the "AMBIDEXTROUS INSIDE THE PANTS HOLSTER" from holsterman6376 on EBAY, and the "Leather Concealment Gun Holster - M&P SHIELD with or without Laser (#035)" from Holstermonster, also on EBAY, all work, well enough for now.  But I can't wait for a good quality formed holster for concealed carry to be manufactured.

This laser is a great addition to the S&W Shield.  Just keep in mind that finding a proper holster is going to be difficult until enough of them are out there for the manufacturers to respond to market demand.
summary: Love the laser, wishing for a kydex or formed leather holster.

So I've done several single speed conversions - and if you have a freewheel hub, you'd think "hey - this is relatively inexpensive and has 16T, GREAT!"  Wrong.

VERY IMPORTANT TO NOTE: once you install this hub, there is no way to get it off.

This hub does not have the freewheel removing grooves you'd find with any other freewheel. If you use a 2-pin remover, you open up the cap and find that this thing is loaded with tiny ball bearings - the callsign of a very cheap bike part.

The hub spun decently - but it is my strong recommendation that you look elsewhere if you you could ever envision yourself needing to do bike maintenance, replace a wheel, or want your freewheel to last a long time.

reviewText:
Bought 3 of these sleeping bags in 3 different colors for my kids & I. We were going on a yearly school camping trip & would be staying in unheated cabins. Last year my son & I nearly froze as it got down to 32 degrees. I didn't notice that these were all XXL bags when I ordered & my kids are only 7 & 9 years old & I'm only 5' 8" tall so we definitely didn't NEED the XXL but once I got them none of us wanted to send them back! They are a nice wide bag with plenty of room to lay on your side. As I'm a side sleeper, that was super important to me. The mummy bags are very uncomfortable & although I had a nice one last year, the limited room made me more cold. I got 2 of the left side zip & 1 of the right side zip so we could zip them together if we wanted in the future. The pillow area & the tie down around the face is very nice also.

This year the temps got down in the low 30's also but I was super warm & cozy. The bags hold the heat in nicely also so even though I had to get up several times in the night to help kids use the bathroom, my bag was still toasty when I got back in. I would buy these bags again in a heartbeat. The price was affordable & they seem to be really good quality warm bags. I'm very pleased.

reviewText: I bought one of these about 4 years ago. It was the clear version. I used .12 and .2 gram bbs and it was very accurate and easy to use. I probably put 20,000 rounds through it(probably more). I bought another(about 6 months ago) after I wore out my old gun. I got the black colored gun. I was very disappointed when I received it. It is no where near as powerful as my old gun. The bbs drop after about 25 feet. I could hit a target at 50-60 feet with my old gun. This newer gun won't shoot that far unless you aim way up in the air. These guns are good quality, but lack power and accuracy. Also, they really failed with the magazine. You can't keep it loaded anywhere except in the gun. If you barely press the release button on the top of the magazine, the bbs go flying out. The mags are cheap and hard to load compared to others. Overall, this gun is good to learn the basics. I really like my original stinger, but am disappointed with the newer ones I have purchased.

reviewText:
Summary: Great fairly light kickstand that is fully adjustable, it seems like it will work on all bicycles, it works on my Specalized Sirrus.

Use Case: Occasionally installing on my bicycle when I am moving around areas without bicycle lockups.

The Good:
- Easy to install, it clamps on fairly easily with minimal tools and doesnt seem to mar the finish on my bicycles frame.
- The kickstand snaps down and up easily, and positively.
- The kickstand height is really adjustable which makes it easy to install this kickstand on a higher bicycle and a lower bicycle.
- The kickstand is reasonably light for a cost effective aftermarket kickstand.

The Bad:
- I haven't found any issues with this kickstand, it works as designed and seems to be competitively priced compared to other kickstands, and it is reasonably light.

Other Thoughts:
- 5/5 stars this product installed easily on my Specalized Sirrus bicycle, this kickstand is fully adjustable.

Demographics: I am 29 years old, male, live in Minnesota USA. My wife is 33 years old, and we have a toddler son that is 2.5 years old and a baby girl that is 6 months old. I normally do not have a kickstand installed on my bicycle though I like occasionally like having a kickstand installed on my bicycle when I am putting around and exploring parks.

Disclaimer: I received this product for free from the seller\manufacturer in exchange for my fair and unbiased review.
summary: Great fairly light kickstand that is fully adjustable, it seems like it will work on all bicycles, it works on my Specalized Sir

Overview: These earmuffs are fairly big, but they work as stated. Great hearing protection, especially with indoor range conditions.

Pros:
- Easy to use
- Comfortable
- Work very well

Cons:
- Slight delay with microphone
- Relatively big (about the same size as standard muffs)

These were a Christmas gift and I've waited until now to post my review so I have 5 months of use. I was skeptical at first with electronic muffs, but now I'm sold. They are about the size of Radian Silencers (or just about any other non-electronic muff you'll find). Howard Leight makes a thinner version of this, but you lose some of the protection as well. About the only time you'll notice it is when using a scope on a rifle.

With them in place and turned on, you'll hear everything on the range until the shooting starts. Then it's like wearing regular muffs.

If you are on the fence, get them. As long as you aren't looking for a narrow profile, you won't be disappointed.

reviewText:
These are the absolute BEST (and brightest) 'area' lights I have ever seen/used! I have a 500 lumen headlight, but there is no way to see it from the side, and since I commute at night, I like the thought that I can be seen from the side as well! I had quite a few people wondering what they were, complimenting me on them, or just plain shocked when I told them they could be used as turn signals as well! (Till I showed them, of course) I even had a local Deputy Sheriff tell me it was a great idea, then asked me where he could find a set himself for his bike! Aside from being extraordinarily bright, they are also very safe for night riding, helping you stay visible, especially if/when you wander into an area where there is no ambient light (street lights, etc.). That oftentimes happens to me as I'm commuting, and I want to be certain I'm seen, lest I become a hood ornament! I just recently started getting other lights, (since I saw how big of an impact these were making, as far as visibility) and will let you know how that goes. HOWEVER, these lights are VERY easy to install, and the only actual 'tool' I used, was the
clippers to cut the zip ties when I was done! They're even bright enough to be used during the day, albeit they're not as effective. Still, as I said before, they're easy to install, one charge lasts QUITE a while, and they do a great job at keeping you seen (night or day), so get a set! You'll be happy you did!

(UPDATE 6/14/2015:) Just a word of advice to all the present and future owners of this product. It IS very bright and noticeable, one thing though. Even though the light lasts a quite a while, if you don't charge it every night after a ride, (like I forgot to) and the battery dies on you, once you DO charge it again, it won't work. Calm down! I know the problem! I (at first) thought it was the battery in the 'dashboard' (controller). What it REALLY is, is that if the battery dies, you lose the 'pairing' you did when you first installed the product on your bike. What you need to do, is 're-pair' the two again. Just check the instruction leaflet (that's all it needs, and I like that, plain and simple) that came with it. If you lost/misplaced it, here are the directions, straight from the leaflet itself: "To Pair Dashboard with Battery" 1)Press and hold the battery box button for 3 seconds 2)Then press any button on the dashboard. Hope this helps! I'm also going to make sure I charge it after every ride from now on, no sense taking chances!

(UPDATE 6-19-2017)
Well, after about 2 years, the lights are still going, but unfortunately, The wire from the battery (even though I ride a road bike, but in some rougher areas sometimes) wore out and frayed. Though I didn't think they would, (especially after all this time) I decided to ask for a new power wire, and how much they would want. They pleasantly surprised me when they e-mailed me THE NEXT DAY, and told me they would send me a replacement AT NO CHARGE! THAT'S customer service!!!! I wonder what else this company has for sale....?
summary: These are great for getting you noticed, and therefore, not accidentally bumped off the road!

reviewText: now you see and now you dont

I purchased this bike in October, 2014, after seeing one that was purchased locally. Labeled as an XB-300li, it was sold by the manufacturer at $599, with free shipping. I attempted to buy one locally, with dealer support, and was quoted $1299 plus sales tax, and was told it wasn't a very good bike, and I should avoid it and buy something better (and for much more money). Having read many reviews, I knew there was a risk, but for 599, with free shipping and no local sales tax, decided to take it. I have no regrets.

Today, the same bike is labeled as a Trail Maker, and sells direct for $749.00. I would say that's a good value, if you know what you're getting into.

The bad: the seat is unrideable, the grips are uncomfortable, and the entire bike is poorly built. All of these things are fixable, but need to be addressed.

The good: the frame is well-designed, incorporates the electrics quite nicely, and being the one thing that cannot be changed or upgraded, seems very well designed and built. It doesn't hurt that it's a good-looking piece of kit, much better than 90% of the other electric bikes on the market. And the frame itself (at least mine) was straight and true, beautifully welded, a bit heavy for aluminum, but a nice frame for all that.

Out of the box, I trued and tensioned the badly built wheels, and avoided many problems. If you can't do that yourself, you need your local bike shop to do it--it's cheap insurance against issues. The saddle is awful; any decent bike saddle will be better. Plan on one. The handgrips are truly unbearable; my changeout to expensive German ergo grips changed the bike entirely, for the better.

One negative is the lack of sizes--one frame fits all. I'm 6'1", and the crappy suspension seat post would go nowhere near high enough. Being a standard size (27.2) it was easily and cheaply replaced, with one very beneficial result. With the very high seat and long post, I can just barely pull the battery out without moving the seat. If you're 6' or less, plan on moving the seat every time you pull the battery. Having said that, with a bit longer stem, the bike, while a bit smallish frame for me, fits me quite well.

I worked for a while with the original disc brakes, which weren't too bad. But when they needed new pads, and had issues, I elected to upgrade the disk brakes.

The original rear rack was a bit heavy; I left it off at first, but when I needed one, I put on something lighter, a Topeak MTX to mate with a rear set of panniers.

So, bike, with decent motor: $599 flat.

Used saddle: $35.

Seat post: $20.00

Longer stem: $25.00

Tires: $60.00 (wanted urban slicks, not off-road knobbies)

Better (lighter) rack: $75.00

Ergo grips: $25.00

So, for $840 cash, still almost $500 under what the local shop wanted for this self-same bike, I have an exceptionally competent urban warrior.

X-treme tries to sell this as an off-road mountain bike. I wouldn't take this onto single-track, ever. But it's been a great urban warrior, for the better part of a year, that gets me to work everyday without breaking a sweat, and lets me ride 10 miles easily with no strain on a heart compromised by age and cardiac issues. It's a thrill to pass all the local college kids, when I'm really not working very hard. And a 15 mile round-trip, without a lot of effort, seems to leave me with plenty of battery reserve.

I swore up-front I'd never love this bike, but in fact, I do. If you don't know bikes well, you might have issues, but if you do, this can be a revelation. Plan on not having any real support from the manufacturer, but if you're self-sufficient, this bike is an outstanding value.

Maybe I got lucky, but I've been extremely pleased with this purchase.

Update: 12/6/2016

After 2 years of faithful service, the bike died a week ago, following riding it in torrential downpours. It's been fine in wet conditions, but these were exceptional. It appears that the incomplete sealing of the compartment for the controller (behind the bottom bracket) allowed water to corrode the controller. I've ordered a replacement (model # YK70B for those interested) and am hopeful that it will resolve the issue. But even if it doesn't, I'll feel that I've gotten my value out of this bicycle. Until this failure, it was unfailingly reliable every day for 2+ years. For the same money, I could've supported a car for about 3 months. So I remain happy with the purchase, and hopeful that I will return it to service for $90, for another couple of years.
summary: Good value, but not for neophytes.

reviewText: Have read many of the comments from other buyers and U have to remember what U are buying...a small lightweight carry bag intended for what I see as two primary functions:  1.  carry a minimal amount of clubs on a small par 3 - executive style course and 2. carry a minimal amount of clubs from the car to the driving range.  Under these two use conditions this bag functions just fine.  It will stand up "leaning' against a bag stand on the range - the small stiff spine rod in the bag greatly assists this process.  If you carry the bag by the large strap or simply grab the bag near the top it works just fine.  It tips forward if the bag is handled/carried at the middle or lower portion of the bag.  It rates as 4 1/2 stars in my opinion.  My wife and I use one for our small course and to carry a small amount of clubs when just going to the range to hit a few irons or woods.  The bag appears to be made reasonably durable and should last a long time if handled properly.  It will also "fold" almost in half for storage as the spine rod does not go from the top to the bottom of the bag.

The run time is awful, coming in at 90 minutes on high mode, this is 1 ride at night, so i find my self charging it every time that it is used. The light is very small and light weight, at the sacrifice of battery life. It does feel a little flimsy when installed on my seat post, but this is due to the mount being rubber, I do not have a concern of it falling off while riding however. I am not impressed with the brightness, and I feel this is far from 120 lumens. The instructions say "caution: do not stare directly into beam"... this seems to be a little over the top as it is just not that bright. On high, it is noticibly brighter than on medium and low, but I feel like the battery life sacrifice may not be worth it (i still use on high and charge every use, safety first). all that said, if you can get a deal on it (I did not), go for it, it is a decent light. I will try to get one that is brighter, heavier built, with a larger battery next time around.

Update: lowered to 1 star. Used the light daily for 2 weeks for about an hour, and 2 days after riding on wet roads, the light began to act up. The charger port has white corrosion, and there is water droplets behind the lens. My experience may be different than others, but the light needs to be water resistant from waters spray from the back tire. My particular light may have had sealing issues, and most may be fine, but this warrants 1 star for the light. The company gave me a full refund and were very apologetic, so I am trying a different model.
summary: just ok... (Update: not very water resistant)

reviewText: Quality Product

I am a backpack guy. Always have been. As a small business owner and firearms instructor, I need a backpack that will house my laptop, client files, concealed carry gun (or guns....depending on what I'm carrying), and various other small things (pens, flashlights, spare mags, charger cables, etc).  This backpack is perfect for urban (or suburban) uses because it is not a big box on your back like standard issue military gear that looks and feels weird to be carrying around work, town, etc. It's shaped such that all the flat things (laptop, files, etc) sit against your back and the peripheral junk is towards the bottom. This puts the weight closer to your hips and allows it to stand up more when I set it down.
  In the main compartment there is a kind of hidden area for concealed carry or maybe files that you want separated. The other compartments are pretty self explanatory. There is however a pretty cool little compartment at the very top near the handle (one of my favorite features) that has a soft lined compartment that is advertised as the place to put your iPod or iPhone with the ear buds coming out and into your ear. I liten to music via my iPhone, so I can't have it back there in case someone calls as it would be inconvenient to have to take off your backpack everytime you got a call. Actually I guess you could just answer the phone without looking at the screen to see who's calling, but for some reason I don't ever do that.... anyway, I use it for my wallet, keys glasses/sunglasses, etc. Pretty cool little pouch.
  My only complaint is that the little plastic knobs at the end of the paracord attached to the zippers are not very high quality. This is a very small deal and pretty nit-picky but it's a tad annoying so I thought I'd mention it. There are twelve of them on the back pack and 5 of them are either gone (leaving the paracord pull string unconnected) or in various states of falling apart. This is certainly not a deal break as they zippers with the paracord string work fine. Just thought I'd mention it.
  Anyway, I have the black one and absolutely love it. I'm getting the coyote tan one next.

Well,bought my first Army firesteel ever a couple months ago the black handle version. Decided to burn some leaves in my burn barrel and to test out my new tool. I filled the barrel with leaves and then placed a small peice of card board on top of the leaves and then put a presoaked w/vasoline cotton ball on top of the cardboard. Then positioned my firesteel and striker ,pulled the firesteel up and held striker steady for two pulls and the cotton ball started on fire with the second pull. Ok, here it is a couple months later and i decided i liked the firesteel so much i would order two more with the red handles and they will ride on my other two Bowie Knife Sheaths. My only complaint is the two last red firesteels were 1/8 and 1/16 of an inch shorter than the Black Handled one? I measured from where the steel starts out the handle on each piece. The black handle length was 2 1/2 inch the longest of the 3 .The product works great but arrives in various lengths. 4 1/2 stars if i could , great emergency tool. One last word. Ilike the cotton ball Method its easy/fast way to get a flame that will last a few minutes while one is stoking the beginng fire with ALREADY PREPAIRED kindling of various sizes. Now,If one dosent do the cotton ball method i have used Very dry leaves on the forest floor .Pick up a handful and crunch and roll them over a bandanna mayby till you create for lack of better words Fine Dust. The Spark from the Steel lites this so fast you won't know what hit you. But the fire dosent last as long as with vasoline imprenated cotton ball so you have to HURRY and get your fine kindling on your "PREFIRE"One has to practice with this steeland different tenders. I carry a bic and use it Most of the time but when it fails this fire steel sure beats trying to manufacture a bow or hand drill

I tried several versions of IWB holsters including the top of the line latest and greatest hybrid leather and kydex ones. The claims of comfort and concealability of the hybrids is EXTREMELY EXAGERATED.

This pattern of holster (available from various manufacturers in different price ranges) is by far the most comfortable and with a simple untucked shirt easily concealable. Pulls the butt in tight and keeps the grip at the perfect height above the waistband.

If you've been trying to find the right holster and the fancy new hybrid style just doesn't cut it, then give this a shot. It's a classic for the simple fact that it's comfortable and it works.

Good socks, good price.  These seem to be of good quality and are wearing well thus far.

OUT OF THE BOX:

Pulling these out of  the box, I'm not super impressed (however, it is just sand paper).

They are actually very abrasive, but do not leave grit all over your hands which is nice.

They definitely are not the same quality as Talon grips (www.talongungrips.com) but what I like about these is they have small pieces that can be put on the slide, trigger guard, etc. I would combine the talon grip for the frame, and use some of these pieces for the slide or other places you want to put them. Yeah, you'll have some extra pieces but they can always be cut down and used to replace the worn parts on the slide.

I have not put these to the test yet, so after I see how they hold up to sweat, water, dirt, etc. I'll update the review.

NOTE: These do not fit 100% perfect on the 45ACP, as 45GAP is just a little bit smaller..but that does not bother me. There is another version of this grip specifically for 45ACP (just look around for it on Amazon) but I actually like that they are a little smaller than the raised portion of the grip on my 45ACP because there's less of a "lip" on the edges of the sandpaper to get caught/peeled back.

UPDATE:

After putting these grips through an all day torture test, I still don't think they are as good as Talon grips, but they do work. Not raising to 5 stars, but not dropping any either. Some of the little pieces are lifting, however the big ones are staying in place. I also noticed that if you put any pieces at the front of the slide, the heat is going to make the adhesive loosen up a little bit, but I could live without those pieces anyway. All in all not a bad product..I'd buy again

These are very good socks.

Lately, there has been a trend toward printing patterns on socks to imply some sort of high-tech complex compression scheme, when really they are just the same all over with the color scheme being the only difference. These are not like that. I was examining the foot bed today, and each of the honeycomb shapes is woven thicker than the lighter material around them. This allows them to be very thin, yet still provide a surprising amount of cushioning. The thicker honeycombs spread out a bit to the thinner parts when compressed. I'm not sure how they are doing this, but it is really impressive.

I followed the sizing chart and ordered the large for a 10.5 US Male shoe size, and they fit my feet perfectly, with no extra material in the toe bed. This is common for me with socks, and I hate it. I was glad these didn't have that problem.

They have silver embedded in them, which helps retard bacterial growth. A good thing for socks. If it weren't for the expense involved, all socks would have this - at least they should.

The little fluffy heel helps it stay in place. I hate it when my socks slip down under my foot, and these were good about not doing that.

I will say that even though they are labeled as compression socks, they don't really compress very much. I think for that you'll need to find something that covers more of the leg. So, don't buy them for that.

Recommended.

Sean Logue, 2017
summary: Very nice socks that hide well in shoes

It's cool because it fits in a closet in my apartment and easily in my truck bed but most people would struggle carrying the large heavy bag long distances. I suggest making very sure you have it fully inflated as all rigidity is lost otherwise. With this fully inflated I do still experience a bending where I am sitting but it comes with an inflatable pillow thing to jam in the corner...put it in the back corner and you'll be fine. It also seems quite durable. Similar material to whitewater rafts. I got caught in a rapidly leaving tide out in the mangroves and hit quite a few sharp sticks and things and didn't sink.

It actually tracks surprisingly well because of the added length and rudder thing you can put on the bottom. Tracks better than most cheaper end molded kayaks for sure.

The perks of having it oversized are immense. Plenty of leg room (for once) room for a cooler and all my fishing gear without being cramped. I always throw the air pump in the netting compartment also just to be safe.

I. love. this. cooler. I never thought I would really "love" a cooler, but I do. I tell everyone they should get one. I take it with me all the time.

First, it's very lightweight. You can fit groceries or a couple meals in here, with drinks, and it's still about as light and easy to carry as a good reusable shopping bag. It doesn't feel like lugging around a big cooler full of stuff. Second, the size is perfect. It fits great on passenger's side floor in the car, without squishing my passenger. It's very slim, and still holds a lot (however, probably not more than enough for two people). I have so many dietary restrictions that getting food while out is difficult, so I take it with me most days. It's very convenient and reliable. Also, if something spills in it, it is still very easy to just rinse out, despite the cloth exterior.

Third, and most importantly, it works. I traveled with this, driving from Florida to Boston, and filled it full of food and drinks, with frozen water bottles to keep things cold. Without fail, I would arrive at the end of each day with the water bottles still completely frozen, and everything very, very cold. They even stayed solidly frozen well into the next day. I was amazed.

I can't imagine a better product is out there. I'm sure I'll be getting them in a variety of sizes.

reviewText: Its works for me, no problems.

I LOVE this lid.  I originally found the bottle at a target and I was like... oooo multi-drink.  Yeah, I CHUG my water... I do not sip. So the wide mouth Nalgene in general is hard to chug without spilling all over myself, and the "lip guards" help, but they aren't as functional as this is. Finally after years of abuse, the lid cracked after dropping it, while full, on the corner of the lid. I feel like this is expected, it's plastic. But absolutely totally worth replacing. I was devastated to think that I couldn't buy a replacement, so when I found this I was SOOO EXCITED.

I've purchased an additional 4 bottles, from Amazon (because the top is $7.99 and with the bottle it's $10.20) and I use the top on my 32 oz Nalgene. I got a replacement one for the one that cracked, one for my boyfriend after he kept drinking out of my bottle, and two for my Dad to put on his Nalgenes after he saw me using mine and was jealous.

I can't figure out why people don't like it, and why it would get a bad review. I've had it leak when I don't screw the top on all the way (duh). Sometimes if there is a dramatic shift in temperature and the bottle is upside down there MAY be some that comes out of the air flow valve, but other than that I've NEVER had a leak problem that wasn't user error. I take it everywhere and often sleep with it next to me in bed. I don't often use the straw (sometimes when driving) just because I LOVE the "chugger" so much. The key is the perfect size opening and the AIR INTAKE VALVE!!  I can drink practically the whole thing in one go because I don't have to stop to let it breathe, and I can just seal around the chugger and drink.

This is THE BEST lid/top for a Nalgene ever made. It is awesome and I hope they never stop making it. I've had so many people ask me about it once they see me drinking out of it. I just tell them "multi-drink" on Amazon, and they love it too.
summary: I buy this bottle JUST for the lid.

Our son is in watch nirvana!  We recently received several guy-style watches from HiWatch and he really likes their look and feel. He is a teenage car guy type of kid, and these watches are right up his alley.

This is described as a military-style watch with blue coloration and several functions. It is a nice looking watch, and not terrible heavy, though the face of the watch is fairly large at about 1.75 inches in diameter. It keeps decent time, needed to be adjusted by a minute or so every week, but it is quite affordable.

This watch is water resistant but it is not waterproof, even though that word is used in the listing title. The watch specs are "30m, 3ATM" which does not mean you can safely wear it in 30 meters of water... per written standards, this rating does  mean "will easily withstand splashes or brief immersion in water, or getting caught in the rain. However, it is not sufficiently resistant for swimming or bathing". That is OK with us, though the seller should correct the tile to read water resistant not waterproof.

This battery-powered watch keeps good time, is relatively lightweight and is comfortable to wear. The strap adjusts easily to wrist size, and the underside of the watch fits well against the shape of the wrist. Our son finds it to be quite comfortable.

The Amazon listing notes that this watch is covered by a "2 years warranty" with a "2 months hassle-free return policy" and that the "Seller pays for return if item is DOA or not as described"... a great commitment to customer satisfaction. We received this nice watch gratis from the seller and our son put it to use to objectively see how well the watch fit and functioned. My statement here reflects that testing.

If you are looking for a great watch for your teen car-guy, a battery operated watch of this price, size and style, for use as I have described above, then our son would highly recommend giving this watch from Hiwatch a try based on his experience with it.

Very recommended.

Go for it.

reviewText: First, don't add this product to your cart. Does it work, probably, but you'll be broke in no time if you ride daily and use electrolyte replacement tabs in your Camelbak unit. As an avid homebrewer, I'd recommend the product I use for cleaning and sanitizing kegs. One Step No-Rinse Cleanser You get 8 ounces worth of product instead of 8 tablets. 1tbsp of One Step : 1 gallon of water. So you can get by with less than a teaspoon of One Step. Put the One Step in the bladder, add some water, close and shake. Run the solution through your bite tube. Hang to dry. If you need to clean your bite tube, and don't want to spend the big bucks on their cleaning kit, again, take a page from homebrewing and get a draft line cleaning brush. There are several diameters, the one I had on hand at the house fit, search on Amazon for, "Draft Beer Line Hose Cleaning Brush." Not only is it half the cost, but unlike the Camelbak one, it's long enough to clean the length of the tube from one direction.
summary: How (not) to cost effectively clean your Camelbak

reviewText: Must have for mountain biking. I don't ride without them.

I really wanted to like this seat. I road it several times over several days for a total of about 50 miles! The pains in my posterior kept increasing until I could not push myself to ride it anymore. My hips also began to hurt. If this was the only seat in the world I would quit bike riding.

The Hobson seat is fairly creative in design, and contrary to other reviews, it seemed to me to be fairly well made. I had no major issues with the quality of materials or workmanship. The seat is also pretty light weight, and it looks sort of neat.  The problem for me was my sit bones (or the muscles/fat that covers them) just plain hurt on this seat. I made sure that I was positioned just right within the depressions in the pads. I tried repositioning, adjusting and readjusting 20 times or more. I tried sitting more forward, and more back, and more upright, and lower, and higher, and everything in between, but nothing helped. I even gave my bottom time to heal  somewhat between rides, but it quickly remembered what had caused it so much pain 2 days before.

So far this is the worst seat I've ever used. Had to send it back. I previously tried the Ergo Ultimate nose-less seat, and although I ended up returning it, it was much closer to being comfortable than this one.

For reference I am a 58 year old male, a little over 5' 8" tall, and about 170 lbs. People with different anatomies might have a better experience, although its hard for me to imagine how.

I gave this Hobson 2 stars for innovation, even though my bottom is screaming "0 stars"!!! Maybe their other seats are better (or so I would hope).
summary: Amazing that so many folks find this thing comfortable!

Superb look, garbage quality would say it all. Now the details. The bicycle looks indeed great and I would like to give it 5000 stars! But boy they trashed the quality! One would expect some great Italian quality since the mambo-jumbo "accacio" is translated in the advertising like the Italian for steel. They should put in the description the chinese for crap instead. Immediately after assembly I could see 3 major problems:
1) The vertical middle screw intended to tighten the handlebar has a very shallow hex key imprint in the middle, and that will guarantee stripping the screw when tightening the handlebar.
2) The cable from the front wheel break to the brake handle is way too short, some 4 inches too short I would say. That is keeping the cable in a very weird, straight and post-tensioned position, with one leg of the brake pulled close to the wheel on one side. The cable can not be adjusted, the half inch or so screw adjustment is way less than required. And the brake cable is wrapped tight to the handlebar ...
3) The wheel spokes seem to be adjusted when eyeballing the shape of the wheel but it is impossible to really test it. The problem is with the rubber placed on these wheels. The shape of the rubber after inflating the wheels is bulging in a few places more than half of inch! On at least one place I've seen the rubber with a significant diameter less than normal! That will make you feel like riding over big stones while riding on flat pavement, jumping up and down. I will have to remove the crap put there by these chinese manufacturer and buy real tires.

Okay, so my daughter loves her 200 and my GF loves her 200 model - so I went a step up and purchased the model with sleep measurement. The 410 displays is white on black where the other models are black on white. The White on black characters are hard to see in low light conditions, even with the weak backlighting enabled. The sleep measurement is questionable. While I am an android user, I'm still awaiting a good sync program from Lifetrak, which is promised in April 2014. This product has been out way to long to not have an Android app. If I knew then what I know now, I probably would have waited on the next generation model. Users must keep in mind that this device will not measure your steps if your arm doesn't swing as you walk. Don't grab a baby stroller and head around your neighborhood and hope to ring up the paces - same goes for pushing a shopping cart around the gro. store.
summary: okay device, display can be hard to see in low light, sleep measurement is questionable...

The breakdown on how I determine my star rating of a product
5 stars  I love it! It is awesome and I highly recommend that everyone purchase this product!
4 stars  I like it, but there are some flaws. Not everything can be perfect! I would purchase again.
3 stars  It was okay, but I would probably not buy it again unless I had no other choices.
2 stars  There may be worse products out there, but you can definitely find better choices.
1 star  I dislike the product, I wish I had not purchased it and do not recommend anyone else to purchase it.

If my review helped please take a second and click that it was helpful below. My goal is to highlight features and drawbacks that I would want to know about as a buyer, not hype the product for the seller to increase sales. My remarks are sincere and true. reviewText:
I've used the belt twice, and have only added 25lbs, so I cannot speak to its durability.  It is comfortable though.

I have subtracted a star for the following reasons:

Color - I was expecting a darker forest camo.  From every image, the majority of the belt appears to be forest green.  Instead, it is a desert camo, which is more khaki instead of green.  Not a huge fan of the color.  Did this change at some point?

Carabiners - I like the concept of using carabiners and straps.  However, the carabiner receiving latch is jagged when open.  This causes it to get caught on the belt loop when removing the added weight.  This is aggravating and adds to the time it takes to dismount the weight, and feels cumbersome when you are leaning/squatting to remove the weight.

Price - its about twice as much as other dip belts.  It uses straps and carabiners vs. a chain.  The quality of materials seems high, and  I do like this design because it doesn't scrape paint or chip the kettlebells I'm using.  However, the price is still a bit high.  However, this is somewhat justified by the  different options the design allows.

All in all, I am happy with the belt so far.  I do think that Brute Belt should post pictures that more accurately reflect the actual color of the belt.  I also think the belt loop could be layered with a stiffer material or that a different carabiner could be used to avoid the snagging I mentioned.

This DVD has 3 half-hour-ish workouts: upper (25 min), lower (26 min), and core (30 min). In each workout, after a short warmup, she goes through a round (or circuit) of exercises.  There is a modifier in each workout.  In the upper body workout, she uses a band (which I loved since I really enjoy band workouts).  She's worth following even if you stick with dumbbells.  In the lower-body workout, the modifier uses either lower weights or no weights.  In each workout, the first set is 16 reps, the second is 8 reps with 2 counts, the last is 4 reps with 4 counts. There's an on-screen timer and caption for each exercise. The core workout includes Pilates type floor workout without traditional crunches.

Unfortunately, the DVD isn't chaptered, so you can't skip ahead in a workout.  You have to fast forward, if you want to skip ahead.  From the menu, there are options to do voice only, music + cues, or cues only, where Karen only cues the moves. I don't think I even heard the music, so I can't tell you what it's like.  She gives quite a few form pointers throughout the workout, which I like.  She leads the workout with two background exercisers, one who modifies and one who does what Karen does.  When there is a third more advanced option, Karen does it.

For an intermediate exerciser, these are very doable workouts and the modifier really makes them accessible.  I like the no-nonsense, straight forward instruction. The pace is slow enough that you can go heavy with the weights, whatever that means to you.  If I had to describe these workouts, I'd say that they are almost like follow-along paper workouts - no glitz, no chatter, no unique twists, and no big "personalities".

I just received this knife a couple of days ago, so far I really love it. Second, the safety features, well placed easy to use, and I didn't have the problem of the safety lock engaging on its own in my pocket.

Third the knife itself feels sturdy for cutting, I don't know how solid it would be for lateral force, but hey it's a knife, if you need to pry something open get a screwdriver.  The blade is sharp, I tried cutting nylon straps versus my kanetsune 11 layer damascus steel blade and both cut the straps like butter, no complaints there.

Fourth, the clip is nice, very tight fit so no fear of losing, and hides the knife low in pocket, out of sight.

So far I must say I love this knife and would recommend it.  Given I do not put my knives through the rigors that some do, but for everyday uses around house, yard and dive gear/equipment, it works great.

It, so far, appears as advertised, described and as I would expect it to be.

It arrived after some projects, (not well packed for proection in "original box" (?)) --therefore, only unpacked, and looked it over without using it with several bikes of different configurations.

I thought to write this now, since, it's not made for a specific bike, rather is a general, portable stand. I'll update this when I have that experiential feedback. I've built bikes since High School as part-time work as a kid, --some time ago now, to present.

I can't imagine, with this design, it being funcational if not as well made, --it appears as well and appropirately made.

I won't be able to compare to other offerings, yet comment this comparison thought, --just knowking how other manufactures make something look like something else, but not made as well. If someone offers "this" for less, great, let folks know (!) with the A - B, direct comparison determinations.

A couple of immediate observations that may or may not be of issue to someone else is:
  a) the unit cannot be folded or unfolded, (by me), as one might expect (all the way) with the *Tool-Tray attached. The *Tray has to be removed to do so. For me, I'm not sure it's "necessary" for what it is (the Tray).

Moreover, with all the electronic data products around, I'd hate to have someone put their Phone, etc. on it and have all the data *erased on it's SD card, or otherwise the units memory. Remember, the tray is *Magnetized, with a large magnet attached to the back, that will hold a small wrench in place. Don't put any electronic device on it.

  b) *unfolding it, pushing the collar down by hand to extend the two "V" supporting legs was impossible (for me). For what ever reason this might be the case, --tight fit, thick lubricant, no lubricant, I had to push one leg a little bit at a time, or hold the "V" legs with my feet and pull up on the center post. The one leg, little bit at a time worked best, for me. In time this may become less of an issue. However, if you push in one leg alone, you will damage it.

  c) At this point, not having used it, used it for a while, I am concerned with one thing, --one person clamping it in. (Having used air, compressor powerd shop, foot activated clamps while with two hands lift hold/hang and clamp in, I don't see how one person would mount the bike as per the advertised picture.)

I am anticipating, to have to hang it with a cross bar, other bike-part, then clamp it. To then adjust the work height, would, at this time, seem to be ill advised, --work height would be set first. Therefore, this being an assumed one-person process (one can always get help?) or if doing in-field work at a "rally" ... nonetheless, think that part through for yourself. It didn't occur to me until I unpacked it and see how tight it all is (a good thing to be "tightly" made, yet, part of my present concern).

If I can upload some pictures at/upon unpacking it, I will do so here; and, again update my use experience with it which is the most important element.

I make such an issue of this one person thing because, me being a fairly "big-guy", so to speak, don't see a slighter buld person one handly lifting an "average-typical" (?) bike, balancing the free standing -stand, and clamping without a "trip" spring to initally grab the bike on the stand.

I don't see myself, yet, as returning it, but upon first use in the next day or so, that may change.
summary: Aluminum Cycle Pro Mechanic Bicycle Repair Stand Rack Bike by CyclingDeal

reviewText: Horrible Tent.  I'm just glad I only had to pay $60 for this piece of junk.  This tent lasted 7 days from light use during RAGBRAI 2017.  The overall design of the tent is awful.  The setup is pretty easy, but trying to repack the tent and figure out how to fold it back together is a nightmare.  There are a few pictures to show the setup, but nothing on how to repack the tent.  Not even on youtube.  If you make one wrong fold you'll break a tent pole rolling the tent back up. Ok it's heavy, but there's so much more to this.  The leather shell is by far more durable than vinyl.  I'm not exactly a gym rat, but I've been around far more vinyl bags that slowly (or even quickly) became duct tape shell bags.  Natural leather holds up rather well.  What's under that vinyl is even more important.  As someone who really messed up his wrist by hitting the lower (and thus more compact) part of a unpadded heavy bag, the foam layer between your hands (or legs) and the heavy filling is crucial.  This bag does a great job of that.  As an added plus, the bag holds its shape rather well too (not pear shaped).

The included mounting hardware is nice, though I'll probably put it on a stand soon.  The attach points are heavily reinforced, and frankly this whole bag means business.  This isn't some "New Year's Resolution special" designed to outlast a causal user.  This bag is built for use.  You can pay less, but you'll get way less.  This is the bag to get.

I have really gotten into hammock camping and just using them to relax. Before buying this one I've previously had two hammocks and i've given one to my girlfriend and both my siblings. This is the nicest one that I've used so far for a couple reasons. First is that it's a double allowing two people to share it, it's got plenty of room even for two. For one person the sides just come up higher; and you can just lay at an angle or pull the sides down (as they aren't under tension) to easily see out. Second is the quality, it's got a thick and sturdy cloth without being too heavy; along with god stitching and solid attachment points. Third is that it is quite comfortable; hammocks are usually very good but this has even less shoulder and feet compression than my others. Part of that has to be because this is a double with more fabric allowing more sleeping positions and a greater angle to sleep at.

A couple tips for using the hammock
-Lay at an angle to reduce compression, most important at shoulders and feet
-Look into proper setup or at least do some trial and error to find what is most comfortable
  You'll want a decent amount of sag, too little and you'll feel pressured, too much and you'll be folded at the waist
-If you're sleeping in it definitely get a sleeping pad as you can lose a lot of heat through the bottom of a hammock to the air/wind
-If you are camping in one you should get a hammock fly to protect from the rain; there are ones made especially for hammocks but can be pricy (even more than a hammock) but i've been using a UST Tube Tarp, which costs much less and still works perfectly fine.

Overall I am quite happy with this hammock and will certainly be using it for camping and relaxing. The only negative I would note is the price of the rope kit. It's nice to get everything you need in one package but for the price of the rope you could get a hammock strap set which I greatly prefer for ease of setup. I'm not taking a star off for the rope price as it's not required that you buy it and the hammock is seriously my favorite.

reviewText: Basically, I wonder why they make other kinds of socks. I grew up wearing 100% cotton socks my whole life, always having seams irritating my foot, getting blisters from walking on wet socks, and generally hating wearing shoes. These are awesome. There are no seams, practically, they are padded, they stay in place, and they even have extra thick material on the back of the ankle so you don't make a hole from pulling them on, and the back of a shoe won't dig in. And as for keeping your feet dry, well, I can now run miles in them in the heat without having an issue. The only time I wear different kinds of socks is for hiking. I have not owned them long enough to say how long they last, I guess it's possible they could fall apart after a few months, but even though they are cool and comfortable, they feel like they are tightly woven, so I doubt it. If you want low-cut socks, buy these.

The Mojo is a great idea.  We put them out along with our other decoys.  As we get older, carrying all the decoys in and out is becoming a real chore.  (And hunting should never be a chore!) These Baby Mojos--being smaller--are a step towards a less-bulky load.

They seem to work just as well as their parents.  We hunt in the light of dawn, never in the full light of day.  The ducks notice the motion, but not the fake-ness, so they move right in--at least for the first few weeks of the season, then they smarten up.

We feel it's a good thing:  That different species of ducks are available.  In our area of Texas we get all the species that are offered for sale here at Amazon:  Teal, mallard, gadwall.  So we own all of these.

We did have trouble getting the rechargeable batteries to work this year, but after cleaning the terminals well, wings were flapping once again.  One time last year, one of us fell in and a wing was lost in the mud, so its another good thing that parts are available.

We don't use the remotes and think we do just fine without them.  But be aware, that after a few weeks the ducks get pretty savvy and shy away from the Mojos.  So, after a few weeks, either leave the Mojos at home, or just use one--with a remote--so you can turn it on and off.  If you use the Mojo constantly for more than a few weeks, you will see that the birds start to approach the pond, then veer away.

The Perfect Fitness Crunch is a versatile piece of fitness equipment meant to give your body an all around work out. It helps work out your abs, arms (biceps, triceps)  and your legs.

It comes with basic instructions on how to assemble it and a quick user guide with a link to their website with work out tips. The Equipment itself is recommended for people of any height and up to 300lbs. Out of the box it was quick and easy to assemble only 4 screws and the mesh restraint. I was slightly disappointed to see a few of the seems right out of the box had come loose already, however this didn't affect it's usage or assembly.  There is also no way to fold it up to store it so once assembled it is as is.

As a person who hates crunches I found using this a lot more comfortable whether doing it on hardwood floors or carpet. The support system eases the tension and stress in your back allowing you to concentrate fully on your ab workout. As for using it for push-ups and dips unless you have very toned arms that is difficult, it is very sturdy and will hold your weight without a wobble but the extra height added when doing the exercise can be trying.

Overall this is a great affordable piece of equipment definitely worth investing in.
summary: Cheap Functional Piece of Work Out Equipment
