I've used aerosols with little red tubes for 40 years - mostly silicone sprays. I have had the problem of losing the red tube just like everyone else. I finally decided to tkae a matching spray nozzle from an empty can - similar, but different in that the uptake tube that siphons the liquid from the can had a wider opening due to being made from thinner plastic.

Think about a cocktail straw versus a regular soda straw that has the same outer diameter. The cocktail straw is designed to slow down the flow of the drink to the mouth since some people seem to be unable to sip a cocktail from the rim of the glass. The soda straw is just the opposite - to get as much fluid out of a can or glass into your mouth.

Nozzles come in two varieties: either the uptake tube is a part of the can and the nozzle spout fits over it - OR - the nozzle is permanently attached to the spout and the end of it fits into the can's partially sealed opening. This second method is typically used on spray paint cans.

OK, now FORTUNATELY the little red nozzle on the CLP is totally separate from the uptake tube wqhich is oermanently attached to the can.

SO-O-O, you need to find another nozzle like it (since many have used the CLP spray can and probably cursed the first time that tiny red tube was launched into space), so getting one from a used or empty can (or even a full can from an annoyed user) should not be a problem. Ask around at the range.

If you can get the skinny red spray tube also, that would be GREAT because I'm going to have you make that little red tube a permanent part of the nozzle, and to use a thick rubber band to keep the tube with the can.

Get a headless nail, a sewing pin, a piece of wire, or anything else made of metal that will slide in and out of the tube and is almost as wide as the inside of the tube. In other words, thick enough to slide in and out without getting stuck in it.

Slide the metal inside the red tube. It should already have CLP on the inside so it should slide in easy.. Wipe off about 2" of one end of the red tube with rubbing alcohol to remove every bit of solvent on the outside.

The purpose of the metal insert is to keep the inside of the tube free of the Super-Glue (plastic cement, Gorilla glue, etc) that you are going to put on the very end of the red tube. The metal insert should be flush with the end of the tube.  Be careful not to get any glue on the metal insert.

Hold the can horizontally and point the tube straight down at a rag or a few sheets of paper towel you placed beneath it. Take the glue end of the red tube and insert it all the way into the nozzle. While holding the spray tube with your free hand, press down on the nozzle to spray the insert out of the tube.

When it's out of the tube, let go of the red tube and tilt the can to its normal vertical position. Set it off to the side to let the glue dry completely.

Now that the red tube is permanently glued to the nozzle, you can put the nozzle back on the siphon tube and never worry about losing that tube again.

LASTLY, there is a trick to spraying the CLP so that it does not foam up into a ball or oversaturate what yhou are spraying.

Instead of pressing straight down on the nozzle with the tip of your finger, you're going to take the tip of your finger, rest it on top of the nozzle, and gently press down and back on the rear of the nozzle with your finger direcly in line with the red tube.

In other words, you will be gently TIPPING the nozzle down and backwards, as slowly as possible, until the spray starts to come out of the red tube.

ALSO, instead of holding the spray can in a horizontal position, you will hold it vertically and tilt it about 20 degrees forward (as if the can was pointing to the 1 o'clock position on a watch face).

The idea is to tilt the can to let the liquid come out without a lot of pressurized gas behind it. The part of your gun that is to receive the spray should be horizontal so that the liquid stays in place. You want to distribute the liquid by moving the red tube from front to back over the area that needs the treatment.

Going from front to back keeps the spray from traveling beyond the point you want treated.

When done, hold the can vertically on a table top while you gently lift up on the nozzle to remove it from the siphon tube - taking care not to touch or snag the red tube.

Prior to doing all of the above (although you can do it now), you will have stretched a thick rubber band around the lower third of the can. Move the hand holding the can downwards and pull back on the rubber band about an inch or so. With your other hand, hold the nozzle/tube combo by the nozzle and rotate it so that the tube points straight down and then slide it under the rubber band until the end of the red tube rests on top of the lip that is part of the bottom of the can.

This will keep the red tube empty as well as giving it some support to hold it in its vertical position. The reason why you put the rubber band along the bottom third and not around the middle is to keep from bending the tube and also applying pressure against the joint where the tube was glued to the nozzle.

To remove and replace the nozzle, simply reverse the process listed above.

When storing the can, always make sure to have the tube facing upwards or to the front to prevent it from being accidentally removed from under the rubber band.
summary: How to deal with that pesky spray can and spray tube

The Saris Hottie Bike Stand is very easy to assemble. There are minimal parts involved. The holes drilled in the parts for screws were very accurately placed, making assembly a snap. As with all Saris products I've owned, it is built with very high quality parts and is aesthetically pleasing enough to use indoors without being ashamed for it to be seen. The only difficulty I had in assembly was installing the lower bike supports in the mid-position, which actually straddles the upper and lower sections of the rack. I wasn't that surprised that I needed to use a plastic mallet to settle the supports into place. All other pieces were very easily installed. The rack is very substantial and I would have no reservations about the security of it's ability to hold two bikes when on level ground. The rack comes with one shelf that will hold several accessories including helmets in the special slots made for the clasp to slide into. The current price tag certainly would make one pause, but in my opinion, if you invest a significant amount of money in a good quality bike, you probably wouldn't mind investing in a good quality rack to securely hold your bike.
summary: Great Stand ...Eepecially When You Don't Have a Garage & Have to Store Your Bike Inside

reviewText:
I'm starting out at 4 stars, not because it isn't currently deserving of five but it's durability will make it or break it (pun intended).

I received it fast. I bought it "used" but it was basically brand new. It looked like it may have been used as a demo model that nobody picked up or handled. The only thing that clued you was the cut and resealed plastic. Otherwise, not a mark or blemish on it.

It is the perfect size for an EDC knife with a far better edge profile for utility than a traditional hook design while still being adequate for the intended purpose. Even though it isn't a hook, the belly is good enough at the angle to really bite in. The blade edge comes sharp enough and only takes a bit of touch up. But, the edge is very thin. While the blade has a nice utility shape I wouldn't expect it to hold it's edge if you go hacking away on cardboard. Buy a box cutter for that. But, for cutting cordage or through cloth, it would do admirable work.

It has a different way of opening than the "wave" type copies. You can't see it in the picture but there is an extension coming off of the blade on the knife's spine. You sweep the knife forward on the draw stroke to catch the extension on the leading edge of the pocket. It seems counter-intuitive at first but once you get used to it, it's just as fast as the wave style design. What is really nice is the opening "support" at the back edge of the handle by the finger hoop. It locks in place both opened and closed. When opened it does provide a lot of extra control and leverage. But, it's actual purpose for a kerambit is as a pressure point probe. Digging into a nerve cluster or joint with this would suck.

I'll update my review after I've lived with it for a bit and used it.
Super item.  Well made.

This is a very nicely manufactured fishing rod for the money. I have caught a few snook with it and the response has been excellent for a rod in this price range. The overall durability so far has been good.

The negatives would be: the cork grips aren't as robust as I would like. Also the eyelets are very small which is a current trend in newer rods but makes for a snug pass on some leader knots. The reel connector is all plastic which means it will not rust but like all plastic parts most fail long before their metal counterparts. All in all this is a mid-priced rod for value shoppers. I wouldn't recommend it for every purpose but will work well for most.
summary: This is a very nicely manufactured fishing rod for the money

reviewText:
This is a longer, thinner tent.  I'm 6'1" and can stand fine in the middle but have to bend nearer the outside.  I'm able to sleep easily with my feet and head wall to wall.

This tent does have the nice features of the light and swinging door, but does not have a lot of windows or other features.  The video for the Elite line mentions a remote for the light but that is absent in this tent.

Initial setup time took about 20 minutes but I think two adults can set this up in less than ten.

The door is a really nice feature.  It means kids don't fuss with zippers as much, and can also make it quieter for someone to use the restroom at night.  The light isn't terribly bright so probably just right when camping.  The nightlight feature is a dull yellow light that would be good for children.

When these first arrived, I was concerned about their durability and utility. After getting the hang of using them, however, my thoughts changed. With the connectors, you can arrange the umbrella pretty much however you want it. The clamp is good and stable. We were in brutally hot conditions without shade on a really windy day, but we were able to set these umbrellas up on our chairs and beat the heat. They held up well in the wind (I was originally nervous that they weren't going to hold up under sustained 20 mph winds with 30 mph gusts, but they did). I am very pleased with this product. They come with a nice carrying case and folding them up is pretty easy.

Please note that we got the XL version. I feel that if I had not gotten the XL version, they would have been too short and I couldn't have gotten underneath it in my chair. Even the XL version required me to sneak up into my chair from below given the sun conditions we were experiencing. But they provide a nice patch of shade and they don't heat through underneath.

One more thing: These are sun shades, not umbrellas for rain. They would not work well in the rain, so don't buy them as rain umbrellas.

Overall, this is a really well-thought-out product and I am happy with my purchase! We will will be using them again and again.
summary: If you are big or tall, get the XL version

As many have stated, it is a very bright light, no doubt.  Battery life could perhaps be better for a strobe however.  I have no connection to this company, nor did I receive this light at any discount as some other reviewers have.  Why 4 and not 5 stars?  I received what seems to be a de rigueur email from companies now that sell here and elsewhere asking about the product and imploring a 5 star review.  If the product deserves 5 stars, I will give it regardless of that prevalent practice.  However, if they ask, and if I have a problem, however minor, I will inform them.  Obviously they want to know.  What else would they be asking for.  I immediately replied to their email by stating it was a great light but I had two minor issues, one perhaps "normal" operation that could be improved, and another problem.
1.  The charging light does not change color when fully charged.  Perhaps that's just my unit, but I doubt it.  Don't most charging lights either flash while charging and then become steady?  Or are orange, as is this one, and then become green when charged?  Minor quibble, not a big deal at all, but I passed it on.
2.  The mount, which is basically a flexible piece of rubber and thus mounts quickly and is very easy to place, then has a channel in which the light slides.  It seems as if it should then snap in place so it won't come out unless the thumb tab is pressed.  Mine perhaps is not machined properly as it does not push all the way down and thus will not lock in place.

When I emailed the above back to the company, they replied: "Thank you for the valuable feedback."  I'd have to give that reply 1 star.  1 star for replying.  Zero stars for addressing an issue I brought up that could potentially result in losing the light when going over bumps.
summary: A bright light with minor flaws.

reviewText: OK so i don't collect knives so i didn't just buy this because i thought it looked cool. i had just recently bought the m48 survival shovel and i loved that product united cutlery made, so i decided to stick with united cutlery for my next purchase. i had been looking for a knife that would easily attach to a stick like a walking stick without having to use alot of 550 cord to jerry rig something together. i  also wanted this knife to be small with a decent sheath. the knife would go in my wifes bug out bag for her to use like a spear to keep enemy's a good distance away from her. i did my research on the hawk harpoon and bought it. when it arrived i thought the size was perfect and it had just the right amount of weight to it. i attached it to a old mop stick with many different methods of securing the harpoon to the stick. i used 550 cord, zip ties, ss hose clamps, screws, nails, speaker wire, and i used large cable locks. the harpoon held together well for all of them. i tested its strength by throwing it into the dirt, a tree, and at some cardboard boxes to get it to stick. the blade was still in good shape and i couldn't see any damage to the blade. i was happy to see the harpoon had did everything i wanted it to do. the sheath is "so so" it holds the harpoon tight but it can be an issue to get off with just one hand. i probably will never use this knife again in my life but if something does happen i at least know its in my wife's bag and she can use it for protection.

First impression when I mounted it on the weapon is that it looked a little bulky or chunky. Kind of took me sometime to like it and be sure that it was a good fit. Before you use this to fire live rounds you definitely need to make sure you bore sight it. That's where you get a boresight laser and line up the green or red reticle (ARX) the match the laser coming from the bore sight. If you don't do this like I didn't initially, you'll get rounds all over the place and any adjustments you make won't reflect what you just put in. However, once bore sighted, you will be able to make adjustments and see them on paper. I got nickel sized groups at 25 M once I got it zeroed.

I purchased this carrier so I could load my Wilderness Systems Tarpon 120 by myself. I am using this SOT for fishing.  Despite some sideways slippage I was able to load the kayak on our 2015 Forester.  The pads rested against the flat bottom of the kayak.  The pads, being only 12 inches apart, did not grip the sides of the kayak, hence the sideways slippage.  However, when sliding the kayak back off the rack, it slipped to the side of the car and fell to the ground.  This always happened unless the car was on perfectly level ground.  The back pads are very slippery whereas the front pads have a more gripping surface.  Once the kayak is moved off of the front pads, it becomes unstable toward sliding to the side.  If the carrier was wider so that the pads could be moved farther apart to the sides of the kayak, it might work with a SOT.  Another review pointed out the narrow aspect of the carrier and how it does not work well with a fishing kayak.  I returned the carrier.
summary: Doesn't work well for a sit-on-top or boats with flat bottoms.

Ideal for what I wanted it to do, which was remove an extremely heavy layer of tarnish and grime from a vintage Chinese New Year silver rattle necklace with a lot of contours. I have never been able to get this thing clean since I've owned it. I've tried polishing cloths, which didn't even touch it. I've tried attacking it with a toothbrush. Nothing. I just spent about five minutes with one of these wet wipes and it looks a million times better.
These wipes work a phenomenally on Chinese silver, which I believe is heavily alloyed with Nickel and/or Tin. They aren't quite as noticeable on Sterling unless it's really dirty to begin with.
I tried the wipes on a couple pieces of .925 with much less noticeable results. For those, I still prefer the flannel polishing cloths to get the best shine.
I also tried them on some really grubby Copper and Silver dishes. Results shown. Cleaned up the copper but it's going to take some serious elbow grease to get through that patina. And the silver coffee set wiped down to a shine in just a few swipes.
Pretty good product.

Let me start by saying there are so many different solutions out there for those of us that really don't know how much we don't know about fitness or about getting in shape!  I've scoured the internet looking for a solution. My motivator to try this product was the discounted price in exchange for my honest review. Resistance Bands range from $5 to more than $100. This fact alone is a little discouraging so I was happy to have the choice made for me. To say that I'm on the go is a bit of an understatement so I need something practical - Can I do it at home? In the office? In the car? While shopping? Diversity. That's what I need.
One of the cool things about using resistance bands vs weights or machines is the resistance bands aren't complicated. I don't know about you but I look at some of the contraptions at the gym and am completely intimidated. Then talk about diversity - it's in the bag! Literally. There are areas that I really want to make an immediate impact with and I can alter my routine easily! I can have the bands available to me everywhere I go - Anywhere that I make 10-15 minutes just for me!
After using the product I can see how agility or coordination is improving - maybe I've got super hero strength hiding under this jiggle. HA!!  I"m clearly a beginner but I can see benefit to even the most advanced fitness guru!

Started off with mountain bikes and have now switched to road bikes. On both my road bikes I've used SPD pedals and recently bought some new shoes (Vittoria Hora Evo). Shopped around and ended up with the Look Keo 2 Max pedals in black, since everything else on the bike is already black. I did consider speedplay as it was recommended by a few of my friends who had them, but I just did not like the large plate surface that you have to install to the bottom of these road shoes. Walking around is already difficult in the road shoes, why make it any more difficult? I also did not like the fact that you have to keep them lubed. I wanted something simple, so the only choices that came down to were the LOOK, TIME and Shimano. The bike that I was putting these pedals on was full campy, so I didn't want to mix in Shimano, since it'll look out of place. The Campy pedals double the price of these and also heavier too. It came down to TIME and LOOK. I searched through many forums and read through many articles and in the end chose the LOOK. I like how there is more float option with these pedals compared to the TIME.

I love how large the platform is on these road pedals compared to the SPD pedals. I also love how secure it feels when I am "clipped in". I find these much easier to get in than the SPD pedals that I have. It also weighs a WHOLE LOT less! They are also very easy to clip out! It's pretty much the same method to clip in and out as you would if you had the SPD pedals. The only difference is the clip in part where you have to make sure the nose part of the cleats is aligned with the contact point of the pedal.

Installation on these pedals were a bit easier and quicker than the SPD pedals, but once you've done a few pedal installations they are all the same. I wouldn't bother taking it to a LBS to install for 5 or 10 bucks when you can do it yourself! These call out for a 40NM torque, so if you don't already have a torque wrench, I suggest purchasing one on here.

Overall, I am very satisfied with the purchase and I will recommend these to friends who are looking for new road pedals.

These discs are about as flippy as a 10 year old dx disc.  Be careful.  Learn your shots with this disc.  Grow your confidence.  If there is wind, put it back in your bag.  Grab something more overstable like a teebird (NOT BLIZZARD) for wind.  These are great if you know what you're getting, but the changes to the Blizzard disc production setup has also changed their performance.  The first runs of blizzard discs had bubbles in the flight plane.  Innova decided that this was too hard to consistently produce.  Now all of the bubbles are in the rim.  On the downside, that also dramatically hampers the gyroscopic effect that a disc gets from the throwing torque.  These are new run discs. (Bubbles in the rim only)

I wanted to replace galvanized steel thimble with stainless steel one, unpacked the rope from its factory wrapping and first thing that caught my attention is the fact that rope is so loosely twisted and spliced that thimble almost fell out on its own.
It took no effort at all to replace thimble, if holding by thimble and pulling on rope, it all tightens up but when let loose, ends of splicing and thimble are just falling apart.
I can't help but wonder if it can serve the purpose at all, just tossing it around for a while produced more evident deterioration to splicing with sharp ends catching fibers, separating strands and deteriorating rope's integrity further.

I am going to have to splice the rope myself, seal the ends uniformly and secure the thimble against falling out when rope is not under tension.
I need some large shrink wrap so trip to electronic store is first step, plan is to feed two pieces of about 5 inches long shrink wrap onto the rope, make a clean and uniform splice, stretch the rope to seat the thimble and splice properly then seal it in that state by shrink wrap so it cannot get undone when rope is relaxed. If that doesn't do it, two crimped stainless steel rings will, one by the thimble and one at the end of splice.

The rope itself is no better and no worse then one I can find in local hardware store, mediocre splicing job has to be fixed.

Update:
Heat shrink did the trick, if you follow this trick be sure to get correct size shrink wrap, it shrinks to half of its original size, therefore you need
3/4 inch shrink wrap to seal 3//8 inch rope splicing.
Because splicing is larger in diameter then original rope, stop applying heat when there is evidence of snug confirmation to splicing contour.
Let this cool for few minutes then apply second piece over it, this creates fairly thick, rubber like skin over splicing that remains flexible and holds splicing against falling apart when stored loose.
Heat gun is essential for uniform and controlled heat application, if done right, heat shrink will hug rope's contour and prevent it from coming loose, yet remain in flexible, rubber like state, if it gets dry and hard, you got too much heat  on it and need to redo the whole thing with new piece.
My anchor line is now 4 star product that should have been done to higher quality standard at the factory. If there was an advantage in price, it got eaten by having to re do splicing and changing thimble to stainless steel.
summary: Not impressed with quality of splicing

The tent does indeed pack back with all accessories into the carry bag included. I do not camp often, so I wanted a tent that I did not have to waterproof. Because of the claim by Coleman with their Weathertec water proofing, I was more confident in my purchase. I did see the rain bead and run off the tent fabric. But after awhile, the fabric below the rain fly and above the floor tub became saturated and wet to the touch inside. Also, on the very cool nights, this same section became wet to the touch inside the tent. The fabric under the rain fly never was wet and never had condensation in the morning. The ventilation is okay if there is a good breeze, otherwise the sun really heats up the  tent. Since the rain fly is velcroed to tents poles, guywired to ground stakes and attached to tent pole rings with bungee cord, removing the rain fly was not practical. It is really better to be outside the tent to remain cool than to rely on the mesh to keep the tent cool. This was our experience. We had battery operated fans which helped. I returned the tent after one week of use and two rainy nights primarily due to the water issues.

I purchased this brass trap earlier this year.  It is fairly easy to set up and since I already had a heavy duty macro tripod, it can be set up in any position or height.

The only negative with this trap, and the reason I took one star off is that it doesn't catch all the brass.  Conservatively, it catches approximately 80-85% of the casings, but taking that in account, the ones that fail to go into the trap are usually directly underneath the trap or within a few feet with the odd casing flying backwards.

I wouldn't hesitate to recommend this to a friend at all.  It does a good job, and as long as you remain cognizant of where you're standing it should catch most of your brass.

reviewText:
First off, let me start by describing what I'm shooting these through. Any experienced airgunner will tell you that the pellets your buddy shoots through his rifle with great results may shoot like absolute garbage in yours. You just have to buy a few tins and find the one that works best for your air rifle and setup. For me, these turned out to be the best I've used so far.

I'm running these through a Crosman 2400KT Carbine from the Crosman Custom Shop. Mine has the 18" crosman barrel using a TKO muzzle brake, which I highly recommend as it quietens down the muzzle report to almost nothing. For optics I am using an AIM Sports dual illuminated reflex sight, which can be found here http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00CDPE6B4/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o04_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 Without accessories, this air rifle totaled just over 100 bucks plus shipping, so this is by no means a high end air rifle. It's a simple low fps, low maintenance backyard plinker and very small pest popper. Before using these, I ran some oil and cleaning patches through the barrel to get any debris knocked loose so that I could get an honest feel for the pellets. I wanted to set the scale as close to zero as I could so that I can get real data for my review.

The short answer is, for me, these little boogers are fantastic. I fired about 30 shots through my carbine just getting the dot close to home and to get some lead in the barrel, then popped in a new CO2 cartridge and used the next four shots to dial it in at ten yards. After that, I moved the target back to 20 yards and fired four more shots. I could cover the group with a quarter, and remember, I was shooting with a 1x red dot, not a scope. With a scope, these would have probably been easily covered by a nickel. Before using these I shot Crosman premier .22 Hollowpoints and Domed, Crosman standard pointed, as well as all of the Benjamin .22 Pellet Sampler types. I couldn't get the shots to stay anywhere close to consistent with a single one of those pellets. I know some people complain about accuracy problems with pointed style pellets, but that's simply not the case with these little guys. Out of my first 30 shots, I did have 2, maybe 3 flyers who didn't group with the rest of the herd.

Now that we've talked about accuracy, let's talk about the quality of the pellet itself, as well as penetration. These arrived undamaged and the tin was in great condition, for which I was much relieved. I did have to throw two pellets out of the test group because of slightly dented skirts, but it seems to me about 95% of the pellets are in great condition, which is a high number considering I've opened undamaged Crosman tins to find 15-20% of the pellets malformed or damaged. As far as penetration goes, these pellets really drill home. They seem to penetrate extremely well, and it's pretty obvious to me why that is. The points are well formed, have a good bit of material to them, and seem to be perfectly centered along the body of the pellet. I was really impressed by this. High penetration was exactly what I needed for my low fps carbine, because I don't trust the gun to push a flat or domed pellet hard enough to whack the various pests I have to dispose of. These almost guarantee a clean kill on very small critters due to great accuracy and penetration. Due to the lower fps of my air rifle, I can't offer an opinion as to penetration on game as big as a squirrel or rabbit. I just don't feel comfortable shooting something that size with my air rifle, so I apologize that I can't say how well they would do in that regard. Pest birds of medium to small size drop like a rock, though.

Overall, I'm really happy with these, and went ahead and ordered 3 more tins to stock up a bit. As I said before, every air rifle will have pellets it likes and pellets it won't shoot straight no matter what you do. If you're still searching for a quality pellet for yours, I'd say that this is a great pellet to pick up and see, especially at this price point. You may just be blown away like I was. Best of luck, happy airgunning, and always remember to stay safe and be responsible while enjoying the sport. Cheers!
summary: Any experienced airgunner will tell you that the pellets your buddy shoots through his rifle with great results may shoot like a

I have been using this tent on camping trips for over a year now. First up, after pitching the tent I admire it for a while - it looks really good, compact and the orange / grey combo is beautiful. It has performed wonderfully so far. It is very easy to set up: First time, I set it up in the almost total darkness with light from a small lantern in about 5 minutes. Similarly, dismantling the tent is also a quick process. It is very spacious for two average sized people. Of course one can only sit or lie down inside it. There is ample space to keep things such as flashlights, water bottles etc around the bed. The rain fly works great as well. I have used it in 2 nights of constant rain at RMNP, with the inside staying completely dry. I have never had issues with moisture buildup (and puddles of water) inside the tent - the two vents for air circulation are great in this regard. This is a major positive for me as my first experience camping was in a Eureka tent in AK which flooded in the rain, and had constant moisture buildup issues forming puddles. In moderately windy conditions, the tent has been stable.  I purchased two tarps at Rec Equip., cut them to match the base of the tent, taped up and use it as a footprint. The material is of good quality, and looks like it will last. It is quite lightweight after packing up - maybe not for backpacking, but easily fits in a large trunk/suitcase without adding much weight for checking-in on flights. Some issues, which others have pointed out: the stakes are useless, and bend easily. Get good steel stakes. When pulling the poles out of the grommets, the ends come off and it is a pain to insert them back again. There is a mesh "loft" provided, but I have no idea how to fix it on the ceiling. The hooks on the loft do not match up with the loops. I don't camp in extreme heat or in winter, so I cannot speak for its performance in those conditions. Overall, it is a great tent for camping trips for two people (car camping; at campgrounds; nice fall weather...). Highly recommended.

Got the Alpha Dogg call several months ago. Was debating between the latest FoxPro calls but couldn't believe how much they were asking for them. The Alpha Dogg is hundreds $$ less than the FoxPro and performs as good if not better! Small enough to fit in a small backpack or hand carry but loud enough to be used in the widest open of ranges.

The volume of the Alpha Dogg is great! And from of the review I have read on other sites better than some of the FoxPro calls.  I had this call on it's middle setting and it was still loud enough to call across an open field into the wind. At the loudest settings it could be used in the open prairies with ease. And the volume is adjustable on the remote at any time. The Alpha Dogg is very portable and has directional speakers to cover every avenue of approach. The Alpha Dogg also has built in legs to get it off the ground which fold up and help to protect the side speakers when not in use or while transporting.

The remote for the Alpha Dogg is much better than any I've seen from Fox Pro and very user friendly. It's back lit with adjustable lighting. Large display and large buttons and shows the length of time calling and remaining in the call sequence as well as list the different calls in order on the a preset expert mode and shows which one is currently playing. The range on the Alpha Dogg remote is listed as 200 yds and I can verify that this is indeed true if not a little understated. There are numerous calls on the Alpha Dogg and even a few routines that are setup under the expert hunt modes that have varying calls as well as moments of silence and varying volumes built into the routine.

Overall impression: Outstanding Call! Biggest and best bang for the buck. Great Features, Great Volume, Excellent Range on the remote and numerous calls available on the Alpha Dogg as shipped and many more that you can download and install yourself.

Highly recommend!

reviewText:
I have a Nikon scope on my left handed remington 700 bdl with this 2 piece base (purchased locally). The 2 pieces are of different thicknesses. On my rifle, the front base is thinner than the rear base which causes my scope to angle slightly downwards. This isn't obvious until you try to zero in your rifle and I'm sure this is by design as these mounts afterall are designed for this specific type of rifle.

I've taken this rifle to the range numerous times attempting to zero in the elevation and im at the limit of adjusting the scope, which is not a top end model, but also far from the bottom. The result of this problem is that at 50 yards, my shots are about 5 inches high. This means that the front of the scope is not high enough in relation to the rear. Raising the reticle in the scope so that it matches the point of impact would correct this problem, but I cannot adjust it any higher. My options are either to 1) shim the front mount to make it thicker, or 2) replace this product with bases that are more uniform in height, or purchase a seperate ring for the front that is higher than the rear. My rings are identical in height currently. I'm taking this rifle Elk hunting next month and am extremely dissapointed that I cannot get my scope to zero with this base. Also, due to the design of the rifle, I am unable to swap out the front and rear bases. The screw holes on the remington are seperated by different distances, as you can see from the picture of this product, the holes in the bases are also set (as expected) differently. It's impossible to swap them. They may work fine on your rifle / scope combination but on mine they are unusable and I've been fiddling with it for well over a year. I'm probably going to give these a try - http://www.amazon.com/Remington-Integral-Scope-Mounts-Medium/dp/B002IWYAX6/ref=sr_1_1?s=sporting-goods&ie=UTF8&qid=1350328997&sr=1-1&keywords=remington+700+scope+mounts

Or might go with some adjustable mounts so I know I'll be able to get them to work. I'm subtracting major stars for this because for my application, which is the intended one for this product, they are useless. Thankfully they are cheap, so im not out much, except another excuse to go to the range when my new ones arrive.
summary: Front scope mount is too thin, cannot zero scope on Rem 700

reviewText:
I have very mixed feelings about his watch.  Unlike some sports watches, this one tries to look fashionable, with a rather large square body and a really beautiful crystal front.  It is fairly large, about an inch-and-a-quarter by and inch-and-a-half on the face, and a good quarter inch thick.  It comes with a brown leather band that is about 1/2 inch wide.  I can wear this pretty comfortably (am a 6 ft tall man of moderate frame), but my guess is that others would find it to be too big and heavy.

In  terms of being a sports watch tracking activity, it is pretty good, though I can't really judge how accurate the heart rate monitor is.

In general, I found more to dislike about this watch than to like.  It is difficult to set the watch in that there are endless menus you need to go through and it is just time consuming to make a small change.  The watch has a nice display (numbers or a watch dial image) but I found it pretty hard to read in sunlight and impossible at night - the display is not illuminated.

One problem I had is that although instructions claimed it would keep a charge for a week, I found it drained in 4-5 days, even without a lot of active use (e.g. heart rate monitor on).

It connected OK with my phone, but it recorded only basic data.

Overall, I found this pretty disappointing, especially for very high price.  Although you could wear it as a regular watch (it is attractive in my opinion), it really is not a very good fitness watch - basically counts steps and computes distance, measures heart rate, and otherwise works as a basic watch and stop watch.  For half the money , you could have a fitbit and a good fitness watch like a Polar brand watch, used with a heart rate monitor when you need.  The combination would give you a lot more capabilities than this watch  does, which tries I think to be too many things (including a fashionable street watch) but really doesn't succeed well in any one things - it is too much of a compromise.

I would say this watch  is not great but really isn't bad.  I think giving it three stars is a bit generous - It is to me a C- product.  OK, but just barely in that it is just too limited and quite expensive to boot.
summary: Overpriced and limited - A compromise product that doesn't quite make it

reviewText:
I got this knife today,  excited to finally have a Benchmade.

My excitement didn't last long, though.  The first thing I noticed, was the blade is horribly off center.  It's also got far too much lateral play.  I got 2 $13 Sanremu's with the same order,  and both of them were dead center,  and had less blade play than the near $100 Benchmade.  They were also slightly sharper,  and weigh almost a full half ounce more.  I should note that the 2 Sanremu's are the same size as the Benchmade.  Being a bigger guy,  I need something with a little more heft.

I'm actually very disappointed right now.  I really wanted to like the Benchmade,  but when it seems like it's of lesser quality (build/tolerance,  not blade steel quality) than the other 2,  I can't do anything with it,  other than return it and buy something else.  I've collected knives for nearly 40 years,  and honestly can't believe the lack of quality in this knife.  After seeing many posts in blade forums and Facebook groups,  it seems that sadly,  I'm not alone.  Many others I've spoken with have gotten sub-par quality Griptillians.  I can understand getting lesser quality when you buy the lower end knives from any manufacturer,  but this is just unacceptable.  I've never had this problem with any of the Sog, Kershaw, Gerber, Cold Steel, etc....  knives I've owned.  I just wish Amazon had a way to attach images to reviews,  so I could post a picture of just how badly off center the blade is.

*EDIT*
I added a picture into the Customer Images Gallery to illustrate my issue with this knife.

If I'm ever in the financial position to buy a more expensive Benchmade I'll still give them another chance.  I just can't keep this knife,  and couldn't recommend one to anyone.
summary: I guess I'll be the first to give this knife a low rating.

reviewText:
Colmen Even Temp Stove  Good Stove! Controls are not.

I purchased this stove 1&1/2 years ago. Very good stove, bigger then most stove which gives you room for big pots and boils water in a flash compared to my old Colmen stove. The controls for the burners are a bit touchy. Just the slightest adjustment and you get too much heat or not enough. Takes a bit of getting used to. Difficult to adjust in daylight because you can't see the very clean burning flame. I have used it many times and it dose live up to its name Even Temp! The addition of the center burner makes all the difference with no cool spots when using the griddle. I had to buy a different griddle then the one advertised now. It works but no grease catching trey. So to empty the grease after cooking bacon is a dangerous hot task. I think I will purchase the griddle with the removable grease trey that was designed for my Even Temp Stove. I give it Four Stars!
summary: Colmen Even Temp Stove.  Good Stove! Controls not so good.

I ordered this as part of my P90X workout efforts and, having read the (*very helpful*) reviews by other members, I expected it to have a 'new mat' smell. I was not disappointed. It did have a very industrial smell to it. What I did not anticipate was how strong the odor was when you got right down in chaturanga position on it. Wow! The first couple of workouts took some special breathing techniques.

The good news is that the new mat smell has let up considerably - mostly because I left it unrolled for several days so it could air out. Now, with three weeks of use, I barely notice it any more.

What I did not anticipate was the lack of durability. I have used the mat perhaps 10 times, and have not hit it with particularly heavy duty. I weigh ~ 190 lbs, do most of my yoga barefoot, and there are distinct wear spots already showing up. The material of this mat does not have a very durable surface and it tears with normal usage.

In my opinion, this mat is a 're-use' of a foam material designed for some other use. I would gladly give up some of the cushioning for a tougher material.

I don't think that I will be able to get more than another month out of this mat before I have worn a hole straight through it.

I cannot recommend this mat.

reviewText:
Every time I put my beach umbrella in the sand, I'm always afraid that the wind will pick it up and send it flying. I've dug holes in the semi-damp sand and a few good winds whips and the umbrella is wiggling back and forth and getting loose.

So I was really excited to find this. It 'screws' into the sand with some effort. You have to push down with some force while turning but it's not too hard. But once it's in, it is pretty solid. The turn screw at the top holds the umbrella in place tightly. So as long as you hit some semi-damp sand, it is a great solution for getting more traction in the sand.

I'm sure there are other ways to secure beach umbrellas but this is an affordable solution that tucks in the back of your car or van.
summary: It Takes Some Effort But Makes a Difference

I have a Thermos that my grandmother used for a couple decades before giving it to me twenty years ago.  And, it show no sign of failing and I use it a lot!  This Thermos costs a few bucks more than most but should outlast those.

A couple of very minor potential downsides:
* This model is somewhat big -- but, for me, it the perfect portion for lunch.
* My grade school child says it is hard to open, so maybe it's not best for younger kids.

Our family has three Puck Pros, so I sprung for one cable. Even with three Puck Pros it was grossly overpriced. Effectively, it's just a standard USB cable and a separate plastic clip with two metal contact points. The plastic clip is the part you need and what you're paying for. But as others have said, there's really no choice.

After installing a driver from a third party web page onto our Mac, I was able to upload dives from the Puck Pros just fine. I also successfully updated all three Puck Pros to the latest firmware rev (as of the date of this review, 3.33). You need to position the clip properly, but I did not have any issues keeping it on any of the three computers. A green light means the clip is just powered by the Mac, red means it's actually electrically connected to the Puck Pro (if you see red and DiversDiary still can't see the Puck Pro, you may not have fully installed the third party driver. Note that installation of this driver on a Mac required a restart as well). At that point, if the Mac has all the drivers you need, the DiversDiary app can do its magic.

I would recommend not touching it or bumping the clip while updating the firmware, and make sure you have plenty of battery before updating. The firmware updates did not erase any of the data on the Puck Pros, and didn't take very long.

The software is fun to look at and play with, although it's none too stable (it crashes occasionally). That, the ability to update the firmware, and sharing the cable between the three computers made it somewhat worthwhile to purchase one cable in our case. I don't think I'd be very happy buying this if I only had one Puck Pro.
summary: All Functionality Appears to Work Fine on a Mac

I will be in a group of 25 people and be the only one attacked. I have tried everything from deet to all natural essential oils and everything in between. It would not point north, nor does it spin freely so i constantly get W at the north position or sometimes E lol.  Don't rely on the compass,  but a general compass can be used in emegencies if you have a standard watch with hour/minute hands.  For northern hemisphere lay the watch flat in your palm facing up.  If you have trees or a pole,  look a the shadow,  point the hours hand at the shadow line it up, this is pointing at the sun.  Now find the  point between the hours hand and 12 oclock position,  this should be pointing to your south,  and opposite that should be the north.  Of course the sun comes up in the east and sets in the west as well,  so if the sun is low on the horizon you know that it's setting toward the west (in general).  Anyways, lots of write ups on it on the web if interested.

EDIT 12/26/15: I originally rated this at 3/5 because the label inside the bag says it is filled with cotton instead of a synthetic hollow filament, as advertised. I noted this discrepancy directly with the company, and received a prompt reply explaining that the bags actually are filled with the synthetic filament, but that the tags erroneously say cotton due to a translation error with the manufacturer overseas. In addition, the company responded to my concern that the price on Amazon is higher than on the company's website by explaining that they have to do that in the event of low stock on the Amazon site because they are penalized if they run out of product. They generously refunded me the difference between the Amazon price and the seller-direct price.

In the end, I am satisfied that the bags are, in fact, filled with a synthetic filament as advertised EVEN THOUGH the tag says cotton. In light of this and the outstanding customer service I received, I have changed my review to 5/5 stars.

***
Original review 12/10/15
As I have seen a couple other commenters mention, these sleeping bags are NOT filled with some hollow synthetic material. They are filled with cotton. It states this clearly on the tag. That's a pretty major discrepancy between the product described and the product received.

Another possible downside is that the filling seemed...patchy. Like it was uniformly distributed throughout the bag. However, they may be because I had just taken out of the stuff sack for (presumably) the first time since it was manufactured, and it just needed a bit of fluffing. I don't know; I didn't try to fluff it. Considering that the sleeping bag is only rated for 35 degrees F, it may just not have that much loft. It seemed warm enough for such temperatures, but I wouldn't push my luck by trying to use it down to freezing.

I have not properly field tested this yet, as my wife and I each got one (the colors and zipper orientations are accurate, at least) for a future-dated camping trip. However, the stitching and zippers seem of good quality to me. I especially like the no-bind device on the zipper, which keeps the sleeping bag fabric from getting caught up and jamming.

I'm pretty short (5' 5''), but there's plenty of extra space in the foot of the bag to stuff gear, etc. if need be for me. It felt like there was enough room to bed down comfortably for a grown man of average height and weight. The doubles option of zipping the two complementary sleeping bags together to make a spoony sack is pretty neat, and suggests that this product is geared more toward couples with a fairly casual interest in camping a few times a year rather than serious outdoorspeople. Fortunately for me and my wife, that's us to a T.

The stuff sack works well, and I had no trouble getting the sleeping bag down to its originally packed size. It was a a bit lumpier than it was from the factory, but certainly no larger.

Overall, I think this makes a good temperate weather sleeping bag for someone who needs something servicable and affordable. Frankly, I would be giving it at least four stars and maybe five if it weren't for the misadvertisement of the filling.
summary: Fine sleeping bag, but filled with cotton

THESE COMMENTS APPLY TO F63 but should be helpful for the F80 too:

I have been using my new F63 Sole treadmill for two weeks and I am very happy with it. It seems to have quality and features comparable to those of a treadmill I used to use at an exercise club. I am very happy.

Some comments: 1. The side bars and the pulse handles are too low for me (I am 7 feet tall). 2. the pulse handle gives strange results. INSIST ON GETTING THE CHEST STRAP--it is reliable.

Some history: I originally was interested in the Sole treadmill with 3 horse power because Consumer Reports suggested that the F63 would not be powerful enough. The Dick's Sporting Goods salesman, an honest man (bless his heart), convinced me that the F63, with a max speed of 12 mph and 15 degrees, was plenty for me (I am 70 years old and weight under 160 lbs).

The salesman also convinced me to get a 4-year service deal. Normally I don't buy such service contracts but I did this time, given that I intend to use the machine every day for one hour. The cost was $200.

All in all, after 2 weeks, I wish I had bought the machine years ago instead of getting my exercise biking outdoors.

reviewText:
I just finished using this paint to do the inside of a 14' aluminum skiff. Because I used this on aluminum, I had to prep by using a self-etching primer. Using the advice from other customer reviews, I used a little bit of paint tint to darken the gray color slightly. The paint came out darker, yet still had the bluish tint mentioned by other reviews. As said by others', it's crucial to mix this paint thoroughly, otherwise the micro-beads will not be consistent.
  I applied two coats of paint by use of a roller, which came out very smooth and consistent. I was surprised by how thin the paint rolls out for having "grit" in it. A good strategy would be to roll out an area, and go back over it a few minutes later without adding more paint on the roller. I found that this makes the paint more consistent, and distributes the micro-beads a little better. The initial coat did not adhere well in areas where I had applied caulk, but seemed to be fine after applying the second coat. The cure time may be a few days, but each layer was dry to the touch within an hour of application (in about 65 degree weather, in a paint tent).
  I was pleasantly surprised by the finished appearance. While it didn't completely hide small cracks and imperfections, I am confident that it will grip and hold up well. The only reason I did not rate this paint higher was because it is advertised as a true gray, when in fact it is not; and because it requires some serious mixing for proper application. When you think you have mixed it enough - mix it some more. I would definitely use this product again.
summary: A good strategy would be to roll out an area

Bought the Cold Steel Recon Scout 7 1/2" blade last fall after a boatload of research on quality survival knives that can do most anything.  Paid about $120 including shipping.  The Recon Scout lives up to the reputation of solid performace, a blade that keeps it's sharpness and overall toughness.  I like the solid sheath which makes it easy to carry on a belt or backpack strap.  I added a sheath (to attach my Leatherman multi-purpose) to the Recon Scout sheath.  The Recon Scout weight is great for chopping wood as well as splitting wood up to about 4" in diameter.  Trust me when I say I was chopping frozen oak in 5 degree weather this winter with minimal extra effort.  Always use WD-40 when splitting wood as it helps the knife slide through without binding.  Also, always use gloves which absorbs the shock of chopping and may protect your fingers.  Lastly, when splitting wood: always have a solid piece of wood under the wood you are splitting so you do not "ground" the knife.  Grounding the knife is the fastest way of chipping the blade.

More than once the blade flexed as it had to wrap around a knot as I drove the blade through a piece of firewood.
I notched the blade at the handle so that I could use it for fine cutting (kindling and wood shaving).  The black coating is somewhat worn on the blade due to use but, I kinda of like it.
There is no sign of rust and I have been using it (including in the snow), clearing 3" vines, branches and making campfires.  I try to keep the blade clean, dry and WD-40 the blade after every use and when storing.
Always check gear reviews via the nutnfancy website and youtube as the man knows his stuff.
I might get the larger Cold Steel Trailmaster 9 1/2" blade this fall as I would like to cut larger firewood but this knife is so comfortable to carry.
I spend a lot of time in the woods alone and with the Recon Scout I know that there is not a problem I can't handle with any animal short of a bear.  From a survival standpoint, the Recon Scout and a fire starter is all I need to handle a day or a night in the woods.
Very impressed with the Cold Steel product line after getting the Recon Scout.
summary: The Cold Steel Recon Scout Rocks!

Camping near the beach brings up a unique set of camping and gear challenges, one of those is finding stakes that stay in the loosely packed sand of the campsites. After doing research, including reading some of the reviews in here, we decided these were an acceptable money risk - we are budget-ly challenged. I am so glad we bought these. The holes along the stakes allow you to tie a guy line at any point to bury the line deeper to create a sort of 'dead man' anchor but with a stake instead of a special bag you have to dig a hole for, fill and bury. The sand is loosely packed, but we aren't supposed to dig at the campsites. We used these for the big tarp we use and needed something big and strong to take possible wind or someone tripping over a guy line. Last year with wind bursts our tarp guy lines had to be restaked every day - we also had crappy tarp poles that wouldn't stay extended. We put our line at the bottom most hole, and facing the concave side toward the tent, sank the stakes at a 45 degree angle, tops tilting away from the tent. The guy lines went right into the sand, and the stake was buried almost to the top. We did have one stake that bent slightly, but we later discovered there was a tree root underneath...that stake is now covered in pine sap, ick, the stake went right through the root. They held all weekend, were easy to pull out and since we bought 2 sets, we were able to use these to guy line our new lovely Kelty tarp poles as well :) Investing in good camping gear is a must if you plan on camping often, or even just once a year. Good dependable gear that can make or break the trip.

September 18, 2012. I see I forgot to mention that these stakes are very lightweight, almost feels like holding air. 8 stakes hardly weight anything! I have read other reviews since some on serious camper sites, some from folks who used them for Burning Man, where the winds can gust up to 50 or 60 without storms.

reviewText: At 10.5" long, these are some heavy duty stakes that are going to work well with piercing into some of the more rocky ground that we usually hit during our camping trips.  The galvanized steel is plenty durable and the length of these will help in securing it throughly.  The heads have a thick PVC hook and hole that allows for attaching guide lines.  Whether plastic or metal, these will always get abuse due to the fact that this is where you are pounding them into the ground.  While the PVC looks thick and durable, it certainly isn't invulnerable.  I suggest using a rubber mallet and if they do happen to break there is always the possibility of using a flat washer up against the head to wrap the rope underneath as a backup option.  Pleased with these as they are a bit thicker and longer than some of the others that I have currently.

I'm actually not sure that I like this. Self-massagers have been historically disappointing, but after a hard day, I'm always tempted to try yet another one to see if it will actually help out with back and shoulder aches.
After having this for a week or so, I think I have more complaints about it than accolade. First, the product description seems to imply that you can use this product on your own. I tried, and I found that solo operation is both ridiculous looking and feeling. Because of the length of the item, I found that I cannot get it to roll down my back at any comfortable angle. I think this would only be possible were one a contortionist and able to dislocate one or both shoulders. I also found that, solo, I cannot apply the pressure I need.

Another complaint has to do with the "customizability" of the product: it's just... not, really. While you can certainly remove some or even most of the rings, there is nothing on the rod that will set the place of the remaining rings, causing them to move around haphazardly while the product is in use. There *is* a small bit of friction, but there is not a "ring lock" or anything like that.

Yet another complaint involves the structure of the ring-holding rod: it's basically plastic, and not even particularly hard plastic. You can bend this thing pretty easily. Imagine trying to roll a lump of dough with a 2-foot section of steel cable or thin PVC pipe: it flattens the very top of the dough, but then bows out in the middle and compresses on the ends, still leaving a rounded section in the middle of the dough lump. The malleability of the rod essentially makes it impossible to apply the pressure I need to my back and shoulders -- I can't roll out the lumps in my muscles well enough, or evenly enough.

Another: the exercise guide that the product description says the item contains is actually downloadable content, not an actual book or leaflet: so, when you receive the item, there will be yet more to do. And if you're like me, you won't even download the guide, but rather just start using the product on its own.

The one positive is that the product, for what it is, actually feels relatively nice -- better than nothing at all, certainly -- IF you have someone else helping you out. But it's not a miracle massager by any means, as I hope this review has shown. Unless you're super sore, don't expect to melt into a puddle with the Gaiam.

With this adapter and a Yooeur 12X50 monocular, you can photograph distant objects with your cell phone just as though you were using a camera with a long zoom lens.

Included are:

1.  3 iPhone case adapters, you use the one that fits your phone
2.  Ring that attaches to the case adapter and slides over the eyepiece of the monocular
3.  Remote case
4.  CR2032 battery

Preparing the remote:  On one side of the remote is the piece that you lift up to load the battery.  Insert a very small screwdriver or the point of knife into the small slit provided and pry up the top of the case.  This is easily done.  Insert battery and press the top back on the case.

Preparing the camera:  Put the case adapter on the phone and screw the ring into the place provided.  Be very careful that you don't cross thread or over tighten the plastic threads.  My suggestion is that once you have the ring attached to the case adapter that you leave it there and use the case adapter with ring attached only when you want to photograph using the monocular.  The more often you remove and reattach the ring, the more likely you are to damage the threads.

Connect camera to monocular: Put the monocular on the tripod that came with it, a camera tripod, or some other stable object and then slide the ring over the eyepiece of the monocular

You now have the monocular supported and with your cell phone attached ready to shoot photos or video of objects/scenes beyond the reach of the cell phone camera alone.  (You don't have to use a tripod, you can hold it in your hand, but you will get better photos if the phone+monocular is supported.)

To take the photos/video without jiggling the camera, use the remote after pairing it with the camera.  Press the button on the remote to shoot.

Because of the 12X power of the monocular and because the optics are so good, your photos/video will be good.

I was sent a sample of the adapter to use and then review.  My only suggestion to the supplier is to include in the package instructions that show step by step what to do and that are written in easily understood English.
summary: How Use Yooeur 12X50 Monocular As iPhone Zoom Lens

reviewText: I'm 5'10", 155-160Lbs, 32 inch waist, 32 inch pants inseam. The L fits me just about perfectly. This company's size guidance seems accurate. The pants fit somewhere between tights and sweat pants, just about right for winter bike commuting or mountain biking. Initial impressions: these pants appear well made. The pants are made out of a "gridded" fleece. The front is covered with a stretchy, windproof fabric. The outside finish on both the front and back is smooth "softshell". The interior is slightly fleeced. The ankle zippers are baffled, there are two zippered pockets and the waist has a drawstring and elastic. The knees have articulated stitching. The waist does not have a particularly "high back" cycling cut, the are cut a bit more like skiing pants. However, the waist is fairly high on me so coverage in cold weather shouldn't be an issue. The logos and stitching are reflective. The pants seem decidedly warm, I don't think you'll need tights under them if you're putting out a bit of effort. Overall initial impressions: I'm very pleased, they seem like a good deal. I haven't ridden in them yet, but most people on the internet seem to think these work well.

I own and LOVE the .6 Liter myself, which I got from the LL Bean website for $14. It's a little on the smaller size at 0.6L, but it also comes in larger sizes as well that utilize the high-flow bite straw, which delivers a lot of water with only using one hand and does not spill or leak. Google "CamelBak Eddy Water Bottle" and you'll find it. It took just a little getting used to the straw, but I absolutely wouldn't use any other water bottle now.

Whatever you do, avoid this Nalgene On The Fly Water Bottle at all costs.

EDIT (08/10/2013): Someone informed me in a comment that they also had trouble closing the lid of their RED/WHITE bottle, but other colors worked really well. Go figure. It's too late to return now. If you do decide to get this bottle, apparently you should choose a different color.

Totally amazing sleep system.  It's a little heavy when using all parts but the compression sack makes it small enough to pack easily, maybe not the best for high mountaineering where weight is so important.  I used for four nights in NW Oregon in November and was warm, dry, and comfy... Without a tent!  I just pitched a tarp over a Paracord stretched between a couple trees.  I woke up laying in a puddle on the ground tarp but was bone dry.  I'd be confident camping down into the below zero temps with appropriate base layers (remember... Cotton kills).  I'm 6' and 200 lbs... I fit in it well but only have an extra inch or two in the foot.  It's big enough to turn over in but I'd say 6'2" and 250 is about the max... A person that size may be uncomfortable.  The bivy bag is amazing and if purchased separately would be great addition to any sleeping bag.  The bivy bag is a fair amount larger than the other bags.  I plan to get my wife one for her high dollar mountain hardware bag.  This system is very versatile and I'm overwhelmingly pleased with it.  I wish the government made wise choices like this all the time!
summary: Uncle same finally did something right!  Great system.

reviewText:
This is such a nice little backpack that is perfect for day hikes at the nature park.  It's perfect for bringing along lunch, some water, must have first aid supplies for hikes (mole skin, scissors, band-aids), and other items when you really don't need much with you.

And for spending the day touring while on vacation, this is a must have. It's a place to stash a sweater when it gets warmer, tour pamphlets, post cards, souvenirs, and other touristy things we all seem to acquire throughout the day and never have enough room for in our purses or pockets. You can be sure to have a place to carry a pen for writing those post cards to friends and family (so they can at least think you wish they were there) as well stamps so you can mail them.

It folds up nicely to fit in large purses or tote bags or to wear over the shoulder. There's enough room in it when folded for the basics you normally take along with you then if you need more room, open it up and you've got a backpack!

Or, when folded, it makes a great fanny pack to wear around your waist!

Lightweight and folds up small enough to make it easy to pack in your luggage to take along on trips.

Not for schoolbooks or heavy duty shopping trips. But, for a few light items when a traditional, heavier canvas backpack is overkill, perfect.

I received this product free in exchange for my honest and unbiased review.
summary: When You Need A Backpack But, Don't Have Much To Carry

This sheath is an absolute must purchase if you have ordered the CS SF Shovel. The shovel is a fairly sharp out of the box and can whack off a small but stout tree limb in a few hacks. If you were to pack the shovel into a backpack or other bag, it is very possible that it would rip through the material. This sheath prevents that, and also lets you store it without worrying about it surprising you in the closet or tool shed.
We purchased this for a backpacking trip that we were going to need a multi-purpose tool for, and we were not disappointed in how the shovel and sheath held up. Several days of wear and tear from the sheath being on the outside of a pack, and use in removing and replacing the shovel. Everything held up well and there is hardly any signs of the expedition after a wet rag to take care of some mud it picked up.
The sheath is a bit tight, so if your shovel is dirty at all, it will make it slightly difficult to replace into the sheath. A rinse off or wipe with a rag should do the trick for you.
summary: A Must-Have for the SF Shovel.

reviewText:
This is the best lubricant to use on your bike chain for quiet operation and rust protection. It has a deep penetrating action to reach every part of the chain. It even comes with a thin tube that fits into nozzle to apply a few drops to the chain. It will extend the life of the chain and of the gear derailleur systems.

The built in solvents soften and remove dirt and contaminants while displacing water to prevent rust and corrosion. It does not leave behind a layer of grease to collect and hold dirt and sand and act as an abrasive to the bikes chain and gear system.

Tri-flow reduces chain and gear cog wear. It is also great for the rear derailleur to maintain crisp and accurate gear changes and to keep all of the components moving smoothly. It also works on the front derailleur system the same way.

Tri-flow contains petroleum lubricants and Teflon particles so make sure to shake it well before you use it. I use it to maintain my bikes. It has many other applications and just like it states on the label, it is a superior lubricant.
summary: It has a million uses but my bikes love it the best!

I've tried several different kinds of tire levers and I like these- sort of.  They have a sharp enough tip to get underneath most tire beads- many do NOT and are therefore useless for removing a tire.  However, perhaps because of this they are prone to breakage when mounting tires, especially if you have a really stubborn tire/ rim combination.  I had this problem with Michelin road tires on my Campy wheels.  So I use this tire lever for removing the tire and then a Pedro's tire lever (yellow one, unbreakable but too blunt to get underneath the tire bead) for getting that last part of the tire bead onto the rim.  Perfect combination!  Note that with the right tire/ rim combo, these are the only levers you'll need as long as you're patient and know what you're doing.

reviewText: After a recent power outage had us strategically positioning candles about the house, I purchased a four pack of these little puppies as a better alternative for the next zombie apocalypse. These LED lanterns are low cost, functional and cute as can be. I like that there are no buttons or switches to deal with or break - simply raise the top and and you get instant luminary gratification. I wouldn't rely on them in a situation where they would be getting banged around too much (these are not sturdy enough for your bug out bag), but for my intended purpose, they work just fine. Adequate warm light to illuminate a bedroom, highly portable, and compact enough to easily store (each one is just slightly larger than a 15 ounce can). These would also work great as party lights to hang/sit around your patio, or stash one in your vehicle emergency kit in case you need to change a tire in the dark. I would love to see this design in a watertight anodized aluminum housing - it would significantly expand their utility to more rugged environments.
summary: Pull the trigger - inexpensive "light duty" functionality
