reviewText:
I can remember when Galco and Bianchi and DeSantis were the dominant holster makers. Then Blade Tech came along and shooters would argue for hours over leather vs. polymer (kind of like the "1911 vs. Glock" debate). Now it looks like BlackHawk is everyone's favorite Kydex holster maker.

Personally, I love Kydex and I'm a whore for innovation (always better to go with what's best and most effective rather than to wax nostalgic). However, I've never been a fan of their button release. I'd rather have passive retention and survive an encounter by producing my weapon first, than to worry about whether my gun would fall out on Jupiter *if* I did a somersault or cartwheel.

Anyway, with this holster, I finally got over my dislike for the button. Figured I'd just learn to deal with it. But the paddle was just too large for my body. It's a fairly rigid paddle and doesn't flex much to the shape of your body, and I've got about a 32-inch waist.

I think most people will love this holster. It's a helluva value, comes with all kinds of adjustability, and you can see from the positive reviews that it fits most people. However, I just wanted to add a review that warns fit/skinny guys that the paddle is a little on the large side. I've attached some pictures comparing the BlackHawk paddle size with my favorite Fobus paddle holster. You can see that the Fobus paddle is more compact. Also note that the Fobus features a grippy rubbery insert that keeps the paddle in place. The BlackHawk doesn't feature this, but it does have a tooth that digs into your pants and locks under your belt to provide pant retention.

Unfortunately, this model Fobus holster isn't available for the large-frame Glocks. Darn it.
summary: Good for large frames. People, not guns.

reviewText: Great product, will add some weight to your rifle tho

Good sturdy stand. Much bigger than i thought it was. Arrived quickly. A few issues that  cant really be complained about for the price. One, the cushions on the clamp are not fixed, just pressed on probably by hand  and do not stay on under clamping pressure. I had to glue them and clamp them amd now they seem to be there for good. Two, the arm the clamp is on slides into a plastic ring assembly  on the main  body. The arm is smoothish metal, and the ring is smooth plastic. It tighetens with one or two hex screws that mate up with hex nuts in hex recesses on the other side in a raised tab. Be careful with the nuts, they will fall  out if you aren't careful and you could lose them, and not be able  to  tighent the ring. It might  be  a  good  idea  to  glue them in place. But, it doesnt tighten down enough to hold the bike in position at any point other than the bikes balance point. The fix for this is this: shimming. You could use inner tube, but the tolerance is pretty tight and it might not fit amd even if it does, it might bite through the rubber, defeating your purpose. I bought plumbimg Teflon  tape and Duck brand self fusing repair tape. I tried the repair tape  first and it has seemed to work so far, it gives a little, but held a 30 lb dumbell solid with me torqing it and im big and strong. The clamp is plastic amd honestly, i wouldnt give it a lot of sun, it might get brittle on you. The quick releases are a little coarsely threaded, making adjusments effective but tricky. The steel is sturdy and the legs are stable at various extensions and at the fullest  they are wide, but unobtrusive. Dont drop anything  on them or step or stand on them, they may warp or break easily. The feet fold flat for balancing and flip up for storage. The clamp hace a little bit of side to side play in it and the retaining screw doesnt tighten down enough  to take up the slop, but i don't know of this will be a problem.  The stand is rated to 66 lbs, i think it will handle that, but of there is a breakage, it will the in the clamp, or the ring that hold it on the body as both are structurally  plastic of some sort. I would not put much more that in it. This says portable, and if you plan to move it by car, it will fit in all but the smallest trunks or back seats, but the fix for the shifting clamp arm basically makes the clamp arm unremovable, so if you do it that way, ot womt fit in as small a space as if you could take it out. The handlebar stabilizer arm is the lowest quality part of  this and even then, its pretty  good, but should be cared for and not subjected to stess as it will bend or break  easily. The straps that allow it to attach to something  work  but the holes that slip around the stud on the other side of the endcap are a little bit stiff, so reaming them out to loosen  them just a little bit will ease their use. Its probably  easier  and better to load the stand by parking the bike in front of it, then lower the clamp down to the top tube, seat tube or post, or the down tube (probably not the best way to hold a bike in this stand, too top heavy unless you have it inverted) , then put the bike in the clamp, then tighten it moderately, then lift the bike  off the ground with your back to the bike and the clamp arm on your shoulder (if you have a heavy bike, if not you can just lift it, or load it in the clamp with it where you want it),  so you can tighten  the quick release clamp to hold the rising arm at the height  you want it. This is perhaps a little easier than trying to put the bike in the clamp and tighten it, since the clamp can require two hands since it is sprinf tensioned  and it is counter tightened with a wing nut.  As far as working on a bike on it, you should take care not to over torque things while the bike is on the stand suspended. You should  break bolts loose before you have it in the stand, then load it, do what you need to do, finger tighten, remove and apply finishing torque on the ground. This is simply because of the plastic clamp and ring issues. Its not a park tool or topeak or pedros, but you aren't paying even half of what those cost, if you need heavy duty and three sigma engineering, you should expect to pay for that, this isn't  that, this is a budget basic work stand and thats the price you are  paying. One more thing,  the tool tray is a sorta nice touch but even at this price, it could have been better done. It is two pieces, main tray body with a magnet (small, good for keeping screws where you want them, but not much more than that) and a bracket that holds it to the stand by clampimg it to the main member. The bracket attaches with two hex screws. The threading is so fine it takes about two and a half weeks to screw or unscrew them with the thankfully supplied hex driver. A simple spring tensioned  clamp would make more sense with something that is supposed to be portable, but the tray is a half moon, so it's  possible  to loosen the screws to let it rotate around and let the stand lay flat for transport of storage. The stamd will also store easily under a bed or other higher standing furniture, or a closet or corner.
 If you want to solve the clamp arm rotation  problem without making the arm permanently attached to the stand i just figured out  a way to do that. Get the larger  work clamps you use for holding glued pieces together the kind that have a screw or trigger  tightening mechanism and one clamp arm is fixed  and the other slides along a long rail. Tighten one clamp onto the stands clamp arm on the end that sticks out of the ring after you insert it through. The rail should be on the side that you are trying to prevent motion in. Using another or two other clamps tightly around  the stands vertical  main main tube so that the rail or rails brace the rail from the first, preventing it from rotating.  This will allow you  to use  the stand and not have to worry about the bike roating. Hope this iI'ms helpful

 Update 6-24-16. Reducing to three after using the thing. Its sturdy, and the base is stable. The clamp though renders unusabale. Its unstable and hard to use and comes unclamped or the clamp arm srill shifting even after making modifications to it. I woild not reccomend this unless you are working on a lot of kids bikes or you like buying inexpensove stuff that neds finishing. The entire stand is great except the clamp thst holds the bike.the tray is useful amd hold the tools you pit in it. . So if you are looking for something like this topeak or park tool might be the way to go.
summary: You get ehat you pay for and you don't get what you don't pay for. Hard to beat for the price. Be ready to modofy and fix.

This is probably great for some applications, but not as much for civilians like me who need take the holster off and put it back on regularly.  As it comes from the factory, it's tricky to get on and off while standing, and much more so while seated in a car.

It helps to cut off the tooth on the paddle so it doesn't snag your pants, although that's exactly why the tooth exists (so you can draw the gun without a belt on, by snagging the holster on your pants).  It also helps to use a lighter to soften the plastic and remove some of the tension on the paddle, although I can't say how much I might have weakened the paddle in doing so.  Incidentally, relieving the tension also allows the grip of the gun to sit a little closer to the body (about 1/4") and print a bit less in CCW.

It would be nice if Blackhawk could invent a quick-release feature for their SERPA holsters that didn't add 1/2" to the width of the holster, since that makes it difficult to carry concealed.
summary: Needs some tweaks for civilian CCW

Spring time is here and like many who read this review, it is time to get out the patio sets. In the past, my umbrella simply did not have the support that I would have liked, but short of using bricks or concrete blocks, I couldn't find something that worked really well. The large canopy weight bags by Best Outdoor Canopy Weight are a great solution for not only umbrella stands but many other items. Of course, as the name implies these bags are ideal for use with a large canopy, and in this review I'll address how good the are for both use with an umbrella and a canopy.

Let me start with a disclaimer required by Amazon: I received these bags for reduced cost in exchange Karen honest and unbiased opinion. In my case, that means I put the product to normal use  and in cases like these bags  and many times to an extended use. I include these uses in my commentary as well as any problems I may have experienced.

Now that I have that out of the way I can return to what I use the bags for and how I use them. The bags arrived on a Thursday afternoon just in time for a Saturday afternoon family get together. It was a beautiful day and we decided to eat outside. We fired up the gas grill, and I had one of my sons and another guest set up the table with the umbrella. As I noted in my opening, we have had problems finding the right arrangement for our umbrella and the reason for that is that the table is made in my shop but the umbrella was purchased at a local box store. There was no real stand with the umbrella which meant that from time to time a breeze of 5 mph or more could rattle the umbrella in its place or even lift it from the center of the table.

On this day, I had my son use a single set of the canopy weight bags and he quickly figured out how to use them with some spare sand from a patio project and the bags strong strap system. This is very similar to using them with a canopy, so there is really no stretch of the imagination or use necessary. What the canopy weight bag allowed us to have is an umbrella that was now encased between the two weight compartments and this provided not only the strength necessary to keep the umbrella from rattling on the table but also from trying to rise as the wind picked up in the late afternoon. In fact, we set the canopy/umbrella up in an area that would allow the shadow from the umbrella to cover the nearby sandbox used by my two-year-old grandson. He's a great little-redheaded boy that burns in the sun quite easily so having a product that can help protect him is well worth the five-star rating.

I also participate in a number of local events such as car shows and shooting competitions. Having a canopy often means that you can sit in an area that will block the sun and provide some relief, especially during the high summer months in North Carolina. On this occasion, I took all of the canopy weight bags to the local show where I was parking one of my cars. The canopy was set up, as usual, and now I had some real confidence that it would set in place without having to worry about digging a hole for the legs are trying some other rigged contraption for holding it in place. A number of people coming by car not only enjoyed the engine work but remarked on what a great idea the canopy weight bags were for the canopy. Of course, I told all of them I had received the weight bags on Amazon so they received pretty much the same review that I'm posting here.

Let me finish this review by saying that the quality of these bags is very high. The material used for the weight pockets is relatively thick, with good stitching on the edges and especially where there would be tension. I like the way the whole product was designed. For use, one simply fills the bag was sand or dirt (depending on where you are using it) and slides the pole or leg into place. When used with a canopy you will need all four support bags. If you are using them for a single umbrella or multiple umbrellas then you can use them individually or in groups.
summary: Very nice product that works better than expected
